Additional-information.Summary: Factor-level insights drive supply chain stability
Additional-information.Description: Supply Chain Stability Index Factor Contributions is a comprehensive dataset that captures the driving forces behind supply chain stability trends. It aggregates indicators such as 'Freight and Labor contribution,' 'Capacity contribution,' and 'Supply contribution,' each reflecting distinct dimensions of market dynamics. The data is presented in a tabular format, with key fields like date in the yyyy-mm-DD format and a standardized_date field for consistency. By focusing on factor-level measurements, this dataset facilitates targeted analysis of how each component influences overall stability. Businesses and analysts can leverage these insights to detect potential disruptions, allocate resources, and optimize their supply chain strategies. For instance, spikes in 'Freight and Labor' might signal risks in workforce availability or transportation costs, prompting timely adjustments. Additionally, the historical and forward-looking nature of the records supports trend forecasting, enabling companies to plan inventory levels and refine sourcing decisions. With the primary key set as date, the dataset supports precise temporal analyses and the alignment of factor changes with real-world events. The structured approach makes it straightforward to integrate with existing analytics platforms or dashboards. Ultimately, by dissecting the factors contributing to stability, businesses can design resilient supply chain frameworks around their unique operational and strategic needs effectively.
Use-cases: Supply Chain Risk Management: Identify critical factors driving stability and mitigate disruptions proactively.
Operational Efficiency Improvement: Optimize labor and capacity allocations based on factor contributions.
Strategic Planning and Forecasting: Use historical data to forecast trends and inform key decisions like inventory management and supplier selection.

Extracted-text.structure: Data is in a monthly time series format. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured in a monthly time series format with key columns including "column_name" (name of the column), "descriptive_name" (description of the column name), "last_date" (date of the latest observation), "standardized_date" (date of ingestion), "abbreviation" (abbreviation of the column name), and "factor_grouping" (grouping of factors).

Additional-information.Summary: Monthly supply chain factors last date data info v
Additional-information.Description: Supply Chain Stability Index Inputs Latest Reported Date is a monthly aggregated dataset capturing supply chain factor groupings and their respective latest observation dates. This data helps organizations gauge real-time supply chain stability by identifying last available metrics for each factor. Columns in this dataset include “column_name,” which specifies the name of the metric; “descriptive_name,” providing further detail on the metric; “last_date,” indicating the latest reported observation month and year; “standardized_date,” highlighting the ingestion date; “abbreviation,” presenting a short version of the column name; and “factor_grouping,” grouping related metrics. By presenting these factors in a monthly time-series format, this dataset allows users to analyze trends in freight movement, job openings, inventory ratios, transportation costs, and other key indicators. It empowers businesses to predict changes, mitigate supply chain disruptions, and plan contingency measures for uncertain market conditions. Additionally, it supports cross-functional collaboration, enabling teams from finance, operations, and risk management to make data-driven decisions aligned with real-time insights. Whether used by economists, analysts, or logistics managers, this resource provides critical intelligence to foster economic forecasting, operational efficiency, and supply chain resilience. As such, it can serve as a cornerstone for ongoing monitoring and strategic planning initiatives. Ultimately it is highly recommended.
Use-cases: Supply Chain Risk Management: Businesses can use this data to monitor and manage risks in their supply chain by tracking key indicators such as freight prices, job openings, and inventory ratios.
Economic Forecasting: Economists and analysts can leverage this data to forecast economic conditions by analyzing trends in logistics, capacity, and supply factors.

Operational Efficiency: Companies can optimize their operations by understanding fluctuations in transportation costs and inventory levels, allowing for better decision-making in logistics and warehousing.

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2020 Place of Birth & Marital Status Statistic
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, “census_acs_us_table_3_2020,” from the 2020 American Community Survey (ACS), focuses on place of birth and marital status metrics. It includes variables such as educational attainment, language spoken at home, individual income levels, and poverty status, disaggregated by birthplace. The dataset spans multiple geographic resolutions, from states down to block groups, enabling localized analysis of demographic and marital patterns. Policymakers, businesses, researchers, and social service organizations can leverage these data to explore evolving marriage trends, migration patterns, and population composition. Comprehensive columns detail the age, sex, and race of individuals, in addition to more nuanced data on divorced or widowed statuses. By tracking shifts in marital structures and migration flows, analysts can anticipate and address the future needs of programs targeting spousal benefits, tax credits, and other family-oriented policies. Additionally, these statistics provide insight into assimilation processes among foreign-born populations and can be used to measure the efficacy of initiatives related to linguistic proficiency or workforce development. With coverage across key demographic segments and robust sample sizes, this resource serves as a foundational tool for user-friendly, data-driven assessments. By analyzing geographic shifts and changes in marital patterns, stakeholders can guide policy decisions and market strategies more effectively. Code is B06008.
Use-cases: Identify local or national changes in marital status trends
Evaluate foreign-born population assimilation and language needs
Shape targeted policies, including spousal benefit programs
Conduct regional market segmentation based on marital demographics
Inform resource allocation for urban planning and community services

Extracted-text.structure: The data is structured by various geographic granularities which a user can chose from with each variable being its own column. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by various geographic granularities, including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group levels. Each variable is represented as its own column. Key columns include geographic identifiers (e.g., geo_code, standardized_usa_state_fips_code), demographic information (e.g., age, sex), and health insurance coverage status (e.g., b27001_001, b27002_001).

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2020 data on household/family allocation
Additional-information.Description: The 2020 American Community Survey (ACS) Table 24 includes data that captures how demographic, social, and economic attributes within households are allocated across different geographic granularities, from states to block groups. This dataset highlights household composition and allocation factors, such as race, sex, citizenship, mobility, internet subscriptions, health insurance coverage, rent, and homeowner variables. Each variable exists in its own column, making it easier for analysts to query, combine, or model large-scale demographic indicators. With these allocations, decision-makers can investigate potential correlations among household-level characteristics, identify gaps in resource distribution, and design targeted interventions within the community. The dataset also supports deeper insights into population migrations, differences in living arrangements, and market segmentation across small or large regions. In combination with the provided geographic identifiers (e.g., FIPS codes), users can merge this dataset with external data sources to create advanced analyses of local needs or track changes in the population over time. This valuable resource helps agencies allocate budgets more accurately, informs policy directions, and assists researchers in measuring how social factors evolve. Ultimately, ACS Table 24 is an indispensable tool for comprehensive household and family structure analytics, offering crucial support for evidence-based decision-making. Researchers can examine data coverage thoroughly.
Use-cases: Resource allocation to identify regions with inadequate health coverage
Insurance market expansion in areas with high uninsured rates
Public health program design targeting uninsured populations

Structure: The data is structured by various geographic granularities which a user can chose from with each variable being its own column. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by various geographic granularities, including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group levels. Each variable is represented as its own column. Key columns include geographic identifiers (e.g., geo_code, standardized_usa_state_fips_code), demographic information (e.g., age, sex), and health insurance coverage status (e.g., b27001_001, b27002_001).
Summary: ACS 2020 data on household/family allocation
Description: The 2020 American Community Survey (ACS) Table 24 includes data that captures how demographic, social, and economic attributes within households are allocated across different geographic granularities, from states to block groups. This dataset highlights household composition and allocation factors, such as race, sex, citizenship, mobility, internet subscriptions, health insurance coverage, rent, and homeowner variables. Each variable exists in its own column, making it easier for analysts to query, combine, or model large-scale demographic indicators. With these allocations, decision-makers can investigate potential correlations among household-level characteristics, identify gaps in resource distribution, and design targeted interventions within the community. The dataset also supports deeper insights into population migrations, differences in living arrangements, and market segmentation across small or large regions. In combination with the provided geographic identifiers (e.g., FIPS codes), users can merge this dataset with external data sources to create advanced analyses of local needs or track changes in the population over time. This valuable resource helps agencies allocate budgets more accurately, informs policy directions, and assists researchers in measuring how social factors evolve. Ultimately, ACS Table 24 is an indispensable tool for comprehensive household and family structure analytics, offering crucial support for evidence-based decision-making. Researchers can examine data coverage thoroughly.

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2020 insurance coverage, broad geographies dat
Additional-information.Description: census_acs_us_table_22_2020 is a curated dataset derived from the 2020 American Community Survey (ACS) focusing on health insurance coverage across multiple geographic levels in the United States. It provides comprehensive variables on public and private health insurance, capturing whether populations have coverage through Medicare, Medicaid, employer-based plans, TRICARE, direct-purchase policies, or no coverage. Data can be broken down by age, sex, race, citizenship status, and income, offering vital insights for assessing health insurance needs. With coverage details spanning various granularities such as state, county, ZIP code tabulation area, census tract, and block group, it facilitates micro-level research for targeted interventions. Stakeholders can analyze population counts, identify trends in coverage options, and evaluate disparities among different demographic groups. By revealing areas that lack sufficient coverage or depend on government assistance, policy makers can address healthcare gaps and craft effective plans. Researchers and organizations leverage this dataset to design programs aimed at expanding coverage where it is needed the most, allocating resources strategically, and strengthening public health frameworks. The dataset’s versatility ensures it can support myriad analyses, from localized planning to broad national surveys, ultimately helping enhance healthcare accessibility and equity. Additionally, the consistent format aids integration with broader data pipelines and analytics.
Use-cases: Gain insight into coverage gaps and local insurance needs
Accurately distribute resources and plan health programs
Develop targeted marketing and segmentation strategies
Support urban planning and infrastructure development
Inform policy-making and social program initiatives

name: Supply Chain Stability Index Scores Factors and Inputs

column_metadata.inbound_air_freight_asia: Inbound air freight price indexes measure the monthly price changes of air freight flown from foreign countries into the United States on both U.S. and foreign carriers.
column_metadata.inbound_air_freight_europe: Inbound air freight price indexes measure the monthly price changes of air freight flown from foreign countries into the United States on both U.S. and foreign carriers.
column_metadata.outbound_air_freight_asia: The Outbound Air Freight Index measures changes in rates paid for the transportation of freight from the U.S. to foreign countries on any air carrier.
column_metadata.outbound_air_freight_europe: The Outbound Air Freight Index measures changes in rates paid for the transportation of freight from the U.S. to foreign countries on any air carrier.
column_metadata.job_open_transport: JOLTS defines Job Openings as all positions that are open (not filled) on the last business day of the month.
column_metadata.job_open_mfq: JOLTS defines Job Openings as all positions that are open (not filled) on the last business day of the month.
column_metadata.job_open_rate_mfq: The job openings rate is computed by dividing the number of job openings by the sum of employment and job openings and multiplying that quotient by 100.
column_metadata.job_open_rate_transport: The job openings rate is computed by dividing the number of job openings by the sum of employment and job openings and multiplying that quotient by 100.
column_metadata.whst_invtship_ratio: A ratio derived from dividing the dollar value of inventories by the dollar value of sales. No adjustment is made in these ratios for the markup in sales, which may vary from trade to trade..
column_metadata.mfq_unfillorders: Unfilled orders at the end of an accounting period are equal to unfilled orders at the beginning of the period, plus new orders net of cancellations received during the period, less net sales.
column_metadata.ppi_pr_goods: The processed goods for intermediate demand index tracks price change for fabricated goods sold as business inputs. Examples include car parts sold to car manufacturers and gasoline sold to trucking companies.
column_metadata.ppi_unpr_good: The unprocessed goods for intermediate demand index measures price change for goods that have undergone no fabrication and are sold to businesses as inputs to production.
column_metadata.intermodal_rail_price: Mode of rail transportation that covers the multi-modal transportation of trailers and/or containers by ship, rail, and truck.
column_metadata.freight_truck_price: General freight transportation establishments handle a wide variety of general commodities, generally palletized, and transported in a container or van trailer.
column_metadata.unemp_rate_mfq: The unemployment rate represents the number of unemployed people as a percentage of the labor force (the labor force is the sum of the employed and unemployed).
column_metadata.unemp_rate_transport_whouse: The unemployment rate represents the number of unemployed people as a percentage of the labor force (the labor force is the sum of the employed and unemployed).
column_metadata.unemp_rate_whst_retail: People are classified as unemployed if they do not have a job, have actively looked for work in the prior 4 weeks, and are currently available for work.
column_metadata.fr_carloads: Rail carload traffic is comprised of mostly bulk commodities, such as coal and agricultural products.
column_metadata.fr_im_units: Rail intermodal traffic is comprised of shipping containers and truck trailers moved on rail cars, which transport a large range of goods.
column_metadata.truck_tonnage_index: The Bureau of Transportation Statistics calculates this index based on the American Trucking Association’s monthly Truck Tonnage Index.
column_metadata.u_s_air_carrier_cargo_millions_of_revenu: Freight and mail carried by U.S. airlines in all service classes (schedule and nonscheduled) on domestic flights. A revenue ton-mile is the movement of one ton of revenue cargo carried for one mile.
column_metadata.us_air_carrier_cargo_millions_of_revenue: Freight and mail carried by U.S. airlines in all service classes (schedule and nonscheduled) on international flights. A revenue ton-mile is the movement of one ton of revenue cargo carried for one mile.

Extracted-text.structure: Data is in a monthly time series format. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with each row representing a different combination of PPI indicator and month or quarter. Key columns include "series_id" (internal BLS code), "year", "period" (month or quarter), "value" (index value), and "standardized_date" (date in yyyy-MM-dd format). Quarterly series are denoted with a "Q" at the end of the "series_id".

Additional-information.Summary: Monthly supply chain stability index data factors.
Additional-information.Description: The dataset “Supply Chain Stability Index Scores Factors and Inputs” is a monthly time series resource capturing supply chain metrics, including inbound and outbound freight indexes, job openings, unemployment rates, inventory ratios, and other variables measuring stability. Each row represents monthly or quarterly observations, with standardized dates, factor scores (fa1, fa2, fa3), and cost indicators. This structure enables robust trend analysis and forecasting of economic disruptions. Businesses and policymakers can leverage this data to identify bottlenecks, adjust pricing strategies, negotiate supplier contracts, and proactively address risks. By examining truck tonnage, rail carloads, air cargo, and freight prices, organizations gain comprehensive insights into demand shifts, capacity utilization, and cost pressures across transportation modes. Additionally, the dataset covers processed and unprocessed goods price indexes, contributing to inflation forecasting. Factor scores consolidate multiple variables into holistic signals of supply chain health. Overall, the dataset serves as an invaluable reference for decision-makers seeking evidence-based strategies, enhancing operational resilience and market competitiveness. With its granular monthly detail, users can monitor or forecast emerging disruptions, ensuring timely interventions that protect profitability and sustain customer satisfaction. It ultimately supports continuous improvement and agile responses within dynamic global supply networks, enabling data-driven decisions at tactical, strategic, or policy.

name: Supply Chain Stability Index FA Prediction Interval

Extracted-text.structure: Data is in a monthly time series format. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by month and by commodity group. Key columns include "date", "year", "month", "period", "ppi_value", "commodity_group_code", and "commodity_group_name". Each commodity group has a unique code used by the BLS for standardization.

Additional-information.Summary: Monthly factor scoring in supply chain commodities
Additional-information.Description: Supply Chain Stability Index FA Prediction Interval is a monthly time series dataset that tracks factor scores related to supply chain stability for various commodity groups. Each record includes fields such as date, year, month, period, and ppi_value, along with unique commodity group identifiers from the Bureau of Labor Statistics. By capturing upper and lower bound ranges for multiple factor scores, this dataset allows analysts and decision-makers to assess potential risk levels and volatility in the supply chain environment. With separate upper and lower bounds for Factor Score 1, Factor Score 2, Factor Score 3, and the overall Index score, stakeholders can account for uncertainties when analyzing cost fluctuations, demand shifts, or disruptions. This structure supports detailed forecasts, enabling organizations to plan strategies for procurement, pricing, and inventory management. Additionally, the dataset's standardized format assists market analysts and investors in identifying trends in commodity prices and production costs. By integrating these insights with other relevant data sources, businesses can make data-driven decisions that reduce supply chain disruptions, optimize resource allocation, and capitalize on evolving market conditions. Whether used for financial modeling, operational planning, or regulatory compliance, this dataset offers valuable intelligence for navigating complex supply chain challenges and maximizing resilience.
Use-cases: Price Forecasting
Cost Management
Market Analysis

Additional-information.Summary: Monthly supply chain metrics & stability insights!
Additional-information.Description: The Supply Chain Stability Index Processed Input Data offers monthly time series metrics capturing comprehensive supply chain indicators. The structured table includes columns such as period_begin, period_end, region_type, region, property_type, median_sale_price, homes_sold, inventory, and median_dom, offering insight into real estate dynamics across various geographic granularities. Additionally, it integrates specialized supply chain metrics including inbound and outbound air freight price indexes for Asia and Europe, job openings in transportation, manufacturing, and warehousing, plus inventory-to-ship ratios. These factors collectively track disruptions, gauge workforce availability, and assess shipping performance. The dataset consolidates relevant fields essential for analyzing global supply chain conditions, from freight transportation modes to retail and manufacturing segments. Analysts can leverage this data to identify potential bottlenecks, measure logistic performance, and forecast supply chain demands. Whether for real estate investment analysis, guiding market trend decisions, or informing urban development, the information helps users understand both economic signals and logistics capacity. By combining real estate and freight indicators, this dataset provides a valuable lens into the health of local industries and potential expansion opportunities. Its multi-dimensional coverage ensures it is a powerful resource for strategic supply chain analysis. Users can also model capacity constraints or track economic recovery patterns in various markets.
Use-cases: Real estate investment analysis
Market trend analysis for real estate agents
Policy making and urban planning
Supply chain risk management
Logistics forecasting

Additional-information.Summary: Monthly weather data by zip code since 2014 (cont)
Additional-information.Description: Each month, the dataset provides a comprehensive set of weather measurements aggregated at the zip code level. Historical records dating back to 2014 capture essential climate variables such as average, minimum, and maximum temperatures, precipitation totals, snowfall amounts, and wind speeds. These data points help analysts, researchers, and businesses better understand evolving weather patterns that may affect operations or strategic decisions. For example, real estate developers can compare trends in temperature and precipitation to gauge construction feasibility throughout different times of the year. Insurance providers rely on consistent meteorological data to evaluate risk models, particularly in areas prone to extreme conditions. Financial institutions use weather signals to predict consumer behavior, while regional planners monitor climate trends to optimize infrastructure projects. The standardized monthly time series makes it easier to track significant changes over time. Each record contains a date stamp and geographically relevant identifiers, ensuring alignment with other datasets for deeper cross-analysis. The inclusion of multiple statistical measures, such as median, mean, and percentile values, offers valuable insight into distribution ranges. Overall, the dataset supports applications spanning real estate, risk assessment, resource management, and marketing intelligence, providing consistent and aggregated weather data needed for informed decision-making across diverse industries worldwide.
Use-cases: Real estate market analysis
Economic forecasting and trends
Risk assessment for mortgage lending
Insurance underwriting and climate risk modeling
Infrastructure planning and resource management
Geospatial modeling for business intelligence

Additional-information.Summary: Comprehensive monthly US transportation indicators
Additional-information.Description: US Monthly Transportation Statistics is a robust dataset that compiles a wide range of metrics tracking the performance, utilization, and safety of transportation modes across the United States. Each monthly record captures multiple data points, including airline traffic, freight rail movements, highway vehicle miles traveled, transit ridership, and waterway tonnage. Information such as transportation infrastructure spending, passenger rail data, and automotive sales are also included. This data is structured with columns detailing date, category codes, data type codes, and values, enabling trend detection, seasonal analysis, and cross-modal comparisons. By offering insights into employment figures, price indices, and regional government spending, this resource supports a multidimensional perspective on transportation dynamics. It can help policymakers, public agencies, and private companies anticipate changes in travel demand, allocate funding effectively, and identify emerging market opportunities. Researchers and analysts can study correlations between infrastructure investments, consumer spending, gas prices, and other critical indicators. The breadth of data also underscores its value for evaluating supply chain resilience, monitoring safety trends, optimizing route planning, and improving the overall efficiency of travel networks. Through updates, US Monthly Transportation Statistics fosters a deeper understanding of how economic forces, technological developments, and policy decisions collectively shape the nation’s transportation systems.
Use-cases: Supply chain management and optimization
Market analysis for investment and strategic planning
Economic forecasting and policy assessment
Infrastructure planning and resource allocation
Monitoring safety and compliance across travel networks

Extracted-text.structure: Data contains both monthly and quarterly data, with each row representing a different combination of PPI indicator & month or quarter. Quarterly series are denoted with a "Q" at the end of the "series_id". Additional Structure Details: The data is structured in a monthly time series format, with each row representing a different combination of PPI indicator and month. Key columns include "series_id" (identifying the specific series), "year" (year of observation), "period" (month of observation), and "value" (price index for the item).

Additional-information.Summary: PPI dataset for industry-wide cost trend analysis.
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides monthly and quarterly Producer Price Index (PPI) time series for various industries in the United States. Each row corresponds to a specific combination of PPI indicators and time periods, denoted by a “series_id.” Quarterly series are identified with a “Q” at the end of the series_id, while monthly series focus on monthly price changes. Key columns include year, period, industry_code, product_code, and the index value, which enables analysts to track cost trends over time. By incorporating these data points, users can measure fluctuations in the prices received by domestic producers, which can signal upstream changes in input costs and market dynamics. PPI serves as a crucial leading economic indicator because shifts in producer prices often feed into consumer price changes and broader inflationary patterns. This dataset is especially useful in supply chain management and operational planning, as businesses can project cost behavior for materials and products. Furthermore, financial analysts can leverage these metrics to make informed investment strategies, while policymakers rely on PPI data to gauge industry health and develop targeted interventions. By examining trends at both the monthly and quarterly levels, organizations gain a more comprehensive view of evolving industry cost structures. Such insights inform decisions.
Use-cases: Inflation forecasting
Cost management
Market analysis
Procurement planning

Additional-information.Summary: US metals PPI, tracking monthly price fluctuations
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides monthly producer price index (PPI) readings for metals and metal products within the United States, capturing changes in commodity costs over time. Pulled from official BLS sources, it organizes data by commodity group codes, enabling users to compare price differentials across various segments of the metal industry. Each record aligns to a specific time period, indicated in a YYYY-MM format, and includes fields detailing whether the data is seasonally adjusted or not. The dataset is especially useful for understanding cost trends in raw materials that feed into multiple downstream industries, including automotive, aerospace, construction, and general manufacturing. By analyzing month-over-month shifts, users can identify potential supply chain disruptions, gauge input cost pressures, and anticipate changes in profitability or operations. Coupled with additional microeconomic or macroeconomic indicators, this dataset allows for robust forecasting models and scenario planning. Businesses can refine sourcing strategies, economists can refine inflation outlooks, and policymakers can gain insights into sector-specific cost drivers. With consistent monthly updates, the dataset remains a reliable indicator of metal price movements, facilitating agility in decision-making. Ultimately, it provides an essential piece of the broader economic puzzle, linking materials pricing to global market dynamics. It aids in risk management strategies.
Use-cases: Forecasting cost trends for metals and raw materials
Anticipating potential supply chain disruptions
Developing hedging strategies to mitigate price volatility
Refining sourcing and contract negotiations
Enhancing economic outlook analysis for related sectors

column_metadata.property_type: Type of property (All Residential, Single Family Residential, Townhouse, Multi-Family (2-4 Unit), Condo/Co-op, Single Units Only)
column_metadata.median_sale_price: The final home sale price covering all homes with a sale date during a given time period where 50% of the sales were above this price and 50% were below this price.
column_metadata.median_list_price: The most recent listing price covering all homes with a listing date during a given time period where 50% of the active listings were above this price and 50% were below this price.
column_metadata.median_ppsf: The final home sale price divided by the total square feet of the property (not the lot) covering all homes with a sale date during a given time period where 50% of the sales were above this price per sqft and 50% were below this price per sqft.
column_metadata.median_list_ppsf: The median list price per square foot of all active listings.
column_metadata.homes_sold: Total number of homes with a sale date during a given time period.
column_metadata.pending_sales: Total homes that went under contract during the period. Excludes homes that were on the market longer than 90 days.
column_metadata.new_listings: Total number of homes with a listing added date during a given time period.
column_metadata.inventory: Median days that all active properties have been on the market during a given time period. So the median of the (last day of the period minus the listing aded date), so long as the days active is less than one year and at least 1 day.
column_metadata.months_of_supply: When data are monthly, it is inventory divided by home sales. This tells you how long it would take supply to be bought up if no new homes came on the market.
column_metadata.median_dom: The number of days between the date the home was listed for sale and when the home went off-market/pending sale covering all homes with an off-market date during a given time period where 50% of the off-market homes sat longer on the market and 50% went off the market faster. Excludes homes that sat on the market for more than 1 year.
column_metadata.avg_sale_to_list: The mean ratio of each homes sale price divided by their list price covering all homes with a sale date during a given time period. Excludes properties with a sale price 50%
column_metadata.sold_above_list: The percent of homes sales with a sale price greater than their latest list price covering all homes with a sale date during a given time period. Excludes properties with a sale price 50% above the listing price or with a sale price 50% below the list price.
column_metadata.price_drops: How many listings dropped their price in a given time period.
column_metadata.off_market_in_two_weeks: The total number of homes that went under contract within two weeks of their listing date.
column_metadata.last_updated: Date redfin source last updated the data
column_metadata.standardized_date: Standardized date derived from the period end field.

Investors leverage it to determine optimal entry and exit points, while real estate agents rely on its indicators to refine pricing strategies. Economists integrate these figures into broader macroeconomic models, offering deeper context for potential market shifts. Furthermore, metrics on pending sales, new listings, and price drops offer an encompassing perspective of supply-demand variability, aiding strategic decision-making.

Policy impact evaluation and urban planning
Economic forecasting and macro-level modeling

Additional-information.Description: FRED (Federal Reserve Economic Data) 3-Month Treasury Bill Secondary Market Rate is a monthly or quarterly timeseries that provides interest rate data for short-term US government debt instruments. The dataset includes columns such as date, standardized_date, and value, describing the interest rate at which these T-Bills trade in the secondary market. This measure often serves as a proxy for short-term risk-free rates, reflecting the overall financial market environment and serving as a crucial indicator for monetary policy decisions, as set by the Federal Reserve. The data can also be used to track market expectations, liquidity conditions, and investor sentiment. Businesses in various industries can leverage this data to gauge borrowing costs, evaluate alternative investments, and anticipate changes in financial conditions. Policy analysts and economists utilize the dataset for macroeconomic research, budgeting, and forecasting. The monthly timeseries structure allows for trending analyses over time, enabling identification of cyclical or event-driven fluctuations, and facilitating the establishment of correlations with other economic indicators. This dataset is particularly useful for financial risk management, interest rate analysis, investment strategies, and broader economic forecasting, providing essential insights into short-term interest rates and the overall state of the financial markets. Financial planners rely on this data continually.

Investment Strategy

Additional-information.Summary: Monthly PPI for final & intermediate demand goods.
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides monthly time series measurements of the Producer Price Index (PPI) for goods and services across the United States, focusing on both final demand and intermediate demand categories. It is designed to help analysts and policymakers understand cost changes facing producers before they reach consumers, often serving as an early indicator of inflationary pressures. Each entry is associated with a standardized date and includes detailed metadata such as the specific series identifier, year, period, footnotes, and data ranges covered. The dataset can be disaggregated by different PPI item codes, commodity groups, and geographies, facilitating localized or industry-specific analysis. Additionally, it contains columns that can track vaccination-related information, including FIPS codes, county names, and the percentage of fully vaccinated residents, offering a unique intersection between economic and public health data. Using this structure, stakeholders can examine fluctuations in producer costs alongside vaccination rates and determine how these factors may influence economic recovery or resource allocation. By integrating multiple domains—particularly pricing dynamics and public health metrics—the data enables deeper insights into regional economic resilience and readiness. The standardized format makes it straightforward to compare trends over time, supporting forecasting models and informed decision-making about inflation and public policy interventions.
Use-cases: Analyze producer cost trends for final and intermediate goods to predict potential inflationary pressures
Compare regional variations in PPI with public health data for multi-dimensional resource planning
Support decision-making at various government levels regarding stimulus or targeted incentives
Model economic growth scenarios by incorporating PPI fluctuations into broader market analyses
Track vaccination progress as an additional factor influencing labor capacity and production costs

Additional-information.Description: The CMS NPI Directory Malpractice dataset is a specialized resource that integrates the official Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) National Provider Identifier (NPI) directory with reported malpractice information. By aggregating details about healthcare providers’ professional backgrounds, this dataset reveals potential malpractice incidents, including claims history, penalties, and legal resolutions. Users can reference provider identifiers, location details, and contact information while also cross-checking professional standing and any malpractice alerts. By linking NPI records with malpractice data, stakeholders such as insurers, regulatory bodies, and healthcare networks gain deeper insights into provider quality and history. Furthermore, public health officials and patients can leverage this information to enhance transparency, evaluate medical expertise, and minimize risks associated with future malpractice occurrences. Ultimately, the CMS NPI Directory Malpractice resource serves as an essential reference tool, informing healthcare systems, policy makers, and research institutions about provider accountability, protection of patients, and best practices within the broader medical landscape. This dataset not only helps manage provider credentials but also aims to strengthen health outcomes by fostering accountability, mandating oversight, and reducing legal risks associated with care. By offering a transparent view of provider malpractice records, it serves as a valuable source of data for informed decision-making.
Use-cases: Verifying healthcare provider credentials and malpractice history
Enhancing accountability in healthcare by tracking malpractice claims
Supporting insurers and regulatory bodies in risk analysis and oversight
Empowering patients to make informed decisions when selecting providers
Identifying patterns in malpractice data for research and policy development

Additional-information.Summary: Georgia COVID vaccine data & GA location insights!
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, titled “COVID-19 Vaccine Locations: Georgia,” consolidates information on immunization sites across the state, featuring geographic coordinates and additional data fields critical for public health planning. Each record includes a unique identifier (hud_id), annual tax credit allocation (allocamt), project address (proj_add), total number of units (n_units), and the year the facility was placed in service (yr_pis). Although these columns might initially appear tied to housing structures, they also assist in evaluating community-level healthcare needs and resource allocations. For instance, “n_units” may describe the capacity of a specific vaccination site, while “allocamt” can represent available funding for distribution efforts. Policy makers, healthcare providers, and community organizations can leverage this dataset to identify areas of greatest need, expand provider networks, and boost immunization outreach. By combining demographic indicators, geographic coordinates, and site-specific details, stakeholders can streamline appointment scheduling, allocate vaccine doses efficiently, and track vaccine administration progress over time. Furthermore, the dataset enables health departments to maintain transparency regarding resource allocation, respond swiftly to surges in demand, and adapt strategies to ensure optimal vaccine coverage. This comprehensive dataset ultimately enhances public health decision-making and fosters collaboration to protect Georgia residents. It represents a crucial tool for ensuring equitable vaccination availability statewide.

Assessing the impact of low-income housing on local real estate markets and planning future housing projects

Integrating demographic data to tailor outreach and improve vaccination rates among underserved communities
Evaluating correlations between geographic region, vaccination availability, and health outcomes

Additional-information.Summary: Time-series US COVID-19 vaccine distribution data
Additional-information.Description: The 'State COVID-19 Vaccine Data US' dataset tracks vaccine distribution and administration across the United States. It is structured as a time-series dataset with quarterly snapshots, capturing the latest trends in vaccine allocations, shipments, and administered doses. Each record includes essential attributes such as date, location, vaccine brand usage, doses allocated, shipped, and administered, as well as the number of individuals partially or fully vaccinated. The standardized_date field harmonizes varying date formats for consistent temporal analysis. This dataset also incorporates details about multifamily properties receiving HUD assistance, with each property identified by a unique property_id and geospatial coordinates (location_lat, location_lon). The inclusion of property characteristics and assistance programs enables an integrated approach to analyzing public health interventions alongside housing resources. By combining healthcare and housing data, users can assess vaccine uptake within specific communities and identify potential relationships between residency in HUD-assisted properties and vaccination patterns. Analysts, policymakers, and healthcare professionals can leverage these insights to inform resource allocation, outreach strategies, and targeted support. Ultimately, this dataset supports improved understanding of vaccine accessibility, fosters data-driven decision-making, and contributes to community resilience during and beyond the COVID-19 pandemic. Additional demographic information offers further context, enabling deeper analysis of population segments impacted.
Use-cases: Tracking vaccine distribution across the US in response to COVID19
Identifying areas for potential investment in affordable housing development by analyzing the distribution and characteristics of HUD-assisted properties
Monitoring and improving the quality of life for residents in HUD-assisted properties by tracking inspection scores and demographic data
Allocating resources and funding more effectively by understanding the geographic and demographic distribution of HUD-assisted properties

Additional-information.Summary: Data of US Indian Health Service facility location
Additional-information.Description: US Indian Health Service facility location data offers a comprehensive view of healthcare resources serving Native American populations across the United States. Each record includes essential geospatial details, such as latitude and longitude, facility addresses, city and state identifiers, and ZIP code information. Additional columns capture operational aspects like facility hours, phone numbers, and web resources, providing an up-to-date reference for stakeholders needing to locate or contact Indian Health Service clinics. By showcasing standardized city and county names, as well as FIPS codes, the dataset supports consistent referencing and integration with other demographic or socioeconomic datasets. This listing can assist researchers, government agencies, and healthcare providers in monitoring access to healthcare within tribal communities, identifying gaps in coverage, or planning new site expansions. The data also reveals potential patterns of resource availability, bridging the gap between care providers and underserved populations. Combined with relevant demographic surveys, it can anchor analyses of healthcare disparities, outcomes, and policy impacts. Ultimately, this dataset enables more informed decision-making related to quality of care, patient engagement, and strategic planning for Native American health services, contributing to improved, equitable healthcare delivery for tribal nations across diverse regions. This robust resource helps stakeholders strengthen health outcomes overall.

Additional-information.Summary: Facility-level data on COVID-19 patient capacities
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides comprehensive insights into hospital capacity and patient impact during the COVID-19 pandemic across the United States. Each record represents a seven-day period, including essential fields such as total beds, occupied beds, ICU capacity, and patient admissions. By integrating geocoded facility information, policymakers, researchers, and health officials can monitor healthcare stress levels and identify geographic hotspots requiring additional support. The data captures multi-dimensional metrics, including adult and pediatric bed usage, staffing, inpatient admissions, and suspected or confirmed COVID-19 cases at both standard and intensive care levels. This detailed view into hospital occupancy and patient demographics enables evidence-based interventions and resource allocations. Furthermore, it helps track variations in critical care utilization between diverse regions, potentially informing targeted healthcare policies. The structured format, combined with consolidated facility identifiers, ensures consistent comparisons across reporting facilities. Users can visualize rising or declining COVID-19-related admissions and forecast shifts in clinical demands. Ultimately, this information is vital for strategic pandemic response, enabling timely distribution of supplies, medical personnel, and financial resources where needed. By contextualizing hospital readiness and capacity constraints, the dataset serves as a cornerstone for decision-making and operational planning during public health emergencies. It fosters data-driven collaboration among governmental and private organizations.
Use-Cases: Understanding of hospital capacity and impacts as a result of COVID-19.

Identifying Economic Growth Areas: Businesses and policymakers can use the data to identify zip codes with high SBA loan activity, indicating areas of economic growth and potential investment opportunities.

Industry-Specific Market Analysis: Companies can analyze the data to understand which industries are receiving the most SBA loans in specific zip codes, helping them to target their marketing and sales efforts more effectively.

Risk Assessment for Lenders: Financial institutions can use the data to assess the risk associated with lending in different zip codes and industries by analyzing loan approval and charge-off amounts.

Extracted-text.structure: NCHS has developed a six-level urban-rural classification scheme for U.S. counties and county-equivalent entities. The most urban category consists of “central” counties of large metropolitan areas and the most rural category consists of non-metropolitan “non-core” counties. Three versions of the NCHS scheme are available. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by zip code and includes key columns such as "zip_code" (5 Digit Zip Code), "standardized_date" (Standardized Date), "value" (Measure value), "name" (Measure Name), and "source" (Data Source). The primary key is a combination of "zip_code", "standardized_date", and "name".

Additional-information.Summary: COVID-19 Deaths by County & Race in US - A Dataset
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, titled 'Provisional COVID-19 Death Counts by County and Race,' is produced by the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) to help measure the impact of COVID-19 across the United States with granular breakdowns by race and ethnicity at the county level. The data are structured using a six-level urban-rural scheme that distinguishes between counties in large metropolitan areas and rural, non-core counties. Each entry is keyed by zip code, standardized date, and a measure name. Key columns include county name, FIPS codes, state, total deaths, COVID-19 deaths, and race-specific categories, such as Non-Hispanic Black or Hispanic. Data analysis dates are included, along with start and end date columns for time-based analysis. The dataset additionally includes footnotes indicating data suppression for counts under 10. By analyzing differences in COVID-19 mortality rates across demographic groups, researchers, policymakers, and public health officials can identify disparities, allocate resources, and develop targeted interventions. Businesses, policymakers, and real estate developers may also use these insights to identify potential areas of opportunity or concern when planning new projects or expansions. Overall, this dataset provides essential information for examining the interplay between location, race, and mortality outcomes. Policymakers can utilize these findings to shape health outcomes.
Use-cases: Identifying racial disparities in COVID-19 mortality
Guiding resource allocation and public health interventions
Analyzing the relationship between urban/rural classification and death rates
Supporting real estate and expansion planning through demographic health data
Informing policy decisions to address health inequalities

Three versions of the NCHS scheme are available. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by zip code and includes key columns such as "zip_code" (5 Digit Zip Code), "standardized_date" (Standardized Date), "value" (Measure value), "name" (Measure Name), and "source" (Data Source). The primary key is a combination of "zip_code", "standardized_date", and "name".

The locations of individual buildings associated with each property are not depicted here. The location of the property is derived from the address of the building with the most units. Location data for HUD-related properties and facilities are derived from HUD's enterprise geocoding service. Each record represents aggregated mobility data for a specific geographic area on a specific date.

Additional-information.Summary: Low-Income housing tax credit properties across US
Additional-information.Description: The US Low-Income Housing Tax Credit (LIHTC) Properties dataset provides a comprehensive overview of affordable housing developments across the country. It contains the general locations of LIHTC properties, sourced from the address of the building with the most units, along with key contact information. The dataset is structured with daily records at national, state, and county levels and includes columns such as date, state_fips, county_fips, number_of_trips, population_staying_at_home, and population_not_staying_at_home, describing aggregate mobility patterns in relation to the properties. This information helps stakeholders understand how residents flow in and out of these housing areas and how effectively they meet low-income communities’ needs. In addition to location-based data, users can examine details about tax credit allocations, apartment types, specific population targets (e.g., disabled or elderly), and other federal assistance programs (e.g., HOME, HOPE VI) that may be integrated with LIHTC funding. With extensive column metadata documenting addresses, project and contact details, and geocoding accuracy, the dataset offers granular insights into the administrative, financial, and demographic context of each development. By linking geographic and housing information, organizations can better evaluate program performance, identify gaps, and plan future affordable housing initiatives more effectively and efficiently.
Use-cases: Identify grantee area funding and relevant contact information for Continuum of Care groups
Support public health policy analysis by correlating affordable housing data with mobility and social distancing metrics
Aid transportation and logistics planning by highlighting travel patterns to and from LIHTC properties
Inform retail and service strategy decisions based on changes in consumer behavior near affordable housing developments

The locations of individual buildings associated with each property are not depicted here. The location of the property is derived from the address of the building with the most units. Location data for HUD-related properties and facilities are derived from HUD's enterprise geocoding service. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with daily records at the national, state, and county levels. Key columns include date, state_fips, county_fips, number_of_trips, population_staying_at_home, and population_not_staying_at_home. Each record represents aggregated mobility data for a specific geographic area on a specific date.
Summary: Low-Income housing tax credit properties across US
Description: The US Low-Income Housing Tax Credit (LIHTC) Properties dataset provides a comprehensive overview of affordable housing developments across the country. It contains the general locations of LIHTC properties, sourced from the address of the building with the most units, along with key contact information. The dataset is structured with daily records at national, state, and county levels and includes columns such as date, state_fips, county_fips, number_of_trips, population_staying_at_home, and population_not_staying_at_home, describing aggregate mobility patterns in relation to the properties. This information helps stakeholders understand how residents flow in and out of these housing areas and how effectively they meet low-income communities’ needs. In addition to location-based data, users can examine details about tax credit allocations, apartment types, specific population targets (e.g., disabled or elderly), and other federal assistance programs (e.g., HOME, HOPE VI) that may be integrated with LIHTC funding. With extensive column metadata documenting addresses, project and contact details, and geocoding accuracy, the dataset offers granular insights into the administrative, financial, and demographic context of each development. By linking geographic and housing information, organizations can better evaluate program performance, identify gaps, and plan future affordable housing initiatives more effectively and efficiently.

For tenant-based Section 8, Section 8 Moderate Rehabilitation, and Multifamily Assisted, the housing assistance payment (HAP) is divided by the total number of reported households. Extracted-text.structure: Location data for HUD-related properties and facilities are derived from HUD's enterprise geocoding service. While not all addresses are able to be geocoded and mapped to 100% accuracy, we are continuously working to improve address data quality and enhance coverage. Please consider this issue when using any datasets provided by HUD. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by zip code, with key columns including "zip_code" (text), "standardized_date" (date), "variable" (text), "zip_total" (integer), "zip_population" (integer), "per_capita_total" (double), "mom_growth" (double), and "yoy_growth" (double).

Additional-information.Summary: Mapping HUD's public housing sites & occupant data
Additional-information.Description: This dataset offers geocoded details about homes under the purview of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD). It combines property-level attributes with occupant and spending information, covering aspects such as building names, apartment details, occupant ages, poverty levels, and rent contributions. The data is structured by ZIP code, enabling multi-geographic comparisons and facilitating deeper analyses of local housing conditions. Users can explore occupancy rates, building statuses, average utility allowances, and the number of household members by building, granting clarity into the demographic and economic realities of public housing communities. Additionally, the dataset incorporates crucial geographic identifiers, including census tract and FIPS codes, to support mapping and integration with external data. This helps identify and visualize areas of need, track changes in median household income, or examine long-term public housing trends. Where possible, the data also highlights annual expenditure amounts and federal assistance for each site, offering insights into the extent and distribution of HUD investment. Because geocoding may not always be 100% accurate, users should remain mindful of potential discrepancies when interpreting results. Overall, this dataset provides a valuable foundation for policy creation, urban development, and cross-disciplinary housing research. Researchers can leverage it to inform evidence-based interventions.
Use-cases: Used to identify grantee area funding as well as key contact information of Continuum of Care groups
Real Estate Investment: Identify zip codes with high growth in building permits to target for real estate investments
Urban Planning: Use data to plan infrastructure and services in areas with increasing building permits
Market Analysis: Assess economic growth and population migration trends to inform business expansion strategies

Key columns include employer name, location (address, city, state), number of workers hired, housing details, job title, wage offer, and employment dates.

Additional-information.Summary: US household data tracking pandemic-level changes.
Additional-information.Description: The Weekly Household Pulse Survey Data is a robust dataset capturing real-time social and economic impacts of major events, such as the COVID-19 pandemic, on households across the United States. It collects information about household demographics, food sufficiency, employment status, income changes, health insurance coverage, childcare arrangements, and mental health indicators. Respondents are surveyed weekly, providing a dynamic view into the evolving needs and challenges faced by diverse communities. Geographically tagged at the state or metropolitan level, the dataset illuminates regional variations and trends in housing stability, government assistance usage, and spending behaviors. Analysts can explore how families adapt to shifting job markets, school closures, or healthcare access disruptions. Rich detail on race, ethnicity, income, and family composition fosters equitable policy targeting. This resource also highlights levels of stress, anxiety, and mental well-being. By capturing shifts over time, users can identify patterns in unemployment, risk of eviction, and reliance on social safety nets. With its extensive list of coded variables, Household Pulse Survey Data ensures comprehensive insights into how Americans adjust to crises and opportunities. Its flexible structure suits researchers, policymakers, and businesses seeking timely evidence-based solutions for household resilience and recovery. As living conditions evolve, timely analysis remains vital.
Use-cases: Understand changing social and economic behaviors during pandemics.
Identify geographic areas with elevated need for housing or food assistance.
Support labor market analysis and forecasting of employment shifts.
Evaluate household reliance on government programs such as SNAP.
Assess mental health trends and inform community health initiatives.
Assist policymakers in designing targeted interventions for vulnerable groups.
Guide businesses in adjusting product or service offerings to current demand.

column_metadata.city: Name of City Where Facility is Located
column_metadata.date_updte: Date on Which Record was Last Updated
column_metadata.fac_id: Unique record identifier. The identifier is unique to each record; records located at the same location as another will each have a unique FacilityID.

column_metadata.longitude: Longitude, Decimal degrees for the facility identified by the FacilityID. This is unique to each record.

column_metadata.mode_rail: Indicates if Any Category of Rail Service is Provided at the Facility (Rail_I, Rail_C, Rail_H, or Rail_Light)

column_metadata.near_id_2: Identifier for second transportation facility that is nearby (if applicable) but not a connecting mode.
column_metadata.near_id_3: Identifier for third transportation facility that is nearby (if applicable) but not a connecting mode.
column_metadata.notes: Notes on Service Providers, Connectivity Issues, etc.
column_metadata.point_id: Unique identifier for the transportation facility. The identifier is the same for records of different modes that are located at the same facility
column_metadata.point_lat: Latitude, Decimal degrees for the facility identified by the point_ID. When two or more records are found at the same location, POINT_LAT is the average of the Latitude fields for those records; otherwise same as the Latitude field.
column_metadata.point_lon: Longitude, Decimal degrees for the facility identified by the point_ID. When two or more records are found at the same location, POINT_LON is the average of the Longitude fields for those records; otherwise same as the Longitude field.

column_metadata.t_service: Indicator that service at facility is provided by at least one transit mode (RailCommuter, RailHeavy, RailLight, BusTransit, or FerryTransit)

Extracted-text.structure: Location of individual transit nodes and key information about each. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by testing location, with each row representing a facility. Key columns include facility name, address (street, city, state, zip), phone number, website, latitude, longitude, type of facility, and various service offerings. The data also includes standardized geographic identifiers such as county FIPS codes and state abbreviations.

Additional-information.Summary: US intermodal passenger connectivity node dataset.
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides detailed information about transit nodes across the United States, encompassing various modes such as bus, rail, ferry, airline, and bike-share services. Each entry captures location coordinates, facility names, addresses, phone numbers, websites, and standardized geographic identifiers. The data facilitates analysis of connectivity by highlighting whether intercity or local transportation services operate in a given location. Additionally, the dataset covers specialized codes for intermodal services, referencing parameters like multifaceted commuter links and station-specific attributes. Organizations can pinpoint coverage gaps, optimize travel routes, and assess potential expansions by analyzing the distribution of services. Government agencies, urban planners, and private enterprises can employ this dataset to strategize infrastructure upgrades, ensuring safe, efficient, and equitable transit for communities. It simplifies identifying cross-mode demand, highlighting hub areas where multiple transportation offerings converge. Furthermore, it includes references to facility capacity, operational statuses, and near-by facility identification, promoting integrated planning options. The dataset incorporates contemporary updates to accommodate changes in routes, expansions in capacity, or newly constructed intermodal stations. As a robust resource for multi-faceted transit analysis, it underscores the importance of interconnectivity and fosters development of informed mobility frameworks that better serve travelers, communities, and stakeholders, ensuring comprehensive coverage throughout the nation seamlessly.
Use-cases: Understand transit nodes across the national network.
Identifying underserved areas for targeted facility expansion.
Resource allocation by government agencies and healthcare providers.
Partnership opportunities for community health and mobility initiatives.

Additional-information.Summary: Daily US SBA 7(a) Loan Data Summaries by ZIP Code.
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides daily aggregated information on Small Business Administration (SBA) 7(a) loans by ZIP code, including key columns such as “zip_code,” “standardized_date,” “value,” “name,” and “source.” Because each record is structured with measures indicated in the “name” column, users can identify relevant metrics associated with the lending activities. The presence of NAICS codes allows for industry-level segmentation, highlighting which sectors are securing loans most frequently and how those patterns shift over time. Additionally, these data can be enriched for deeper contextual analysis by linking to other economic or demographic datasets, unveiling correlations between lending activity and broader economic indicators such as employment trends or consumer spending. As SBA 7(a) loans often indicate business expansion or startup initiatives, these metrics can help analysts pinpoint where new economic growth is taking place, and where potential gaps may exist. With daily updates, stakeholders can stay informed about fluctuations in loan approvals and amounts disbursed. Ultimately, this resource is valuable to financial institutions, policymakers, and market analysts, who can use the loan patterns to inform decision-making, support economic development, or target opportunity zones more effectively. The data can be leveraged to uncover growth trends within communities and across industries. Understanding these patterns helps.
Use-cases: Identify geographies with high small business lending activity
Evaluate which industries are receiving the most financing
Assess economic development trends at the ZIP code level
Inform government policy for targeted business support
Spot potential gaps in loan distribution and opportunities for expansion

Additional-information.Summary: Daily US mobility data with insights amid COVID-19
Additional-information.Description: During the COVID-19 pandemic, daily mobility data played a crucial role in understanding how communities responded to evolving health policies. This dataset, focusing on the United States, compiles day-to-day changes in travel patterns, including average distance traveled and the proportion of residents staying at home versus venturing out. Structured at the county level, it highlights potential disparities in testing availability and underscores the impact of official mandates on movement. Key columns track attributes like name (testing location), state, county, full address, phone, operating status, type of test, and operating hours. By analyzing these fields, stakeholders can pinpoint areas most in need of additional testing capacity, direct resources to where they are most required, and coordinate community outreach. Public health officials, government agencies, and academic researchers can utilize these records to develop targeted interventions. This data also supports private sector needs, such as corporate site planning or resource allocation for medical suppliers. Historically, daily mobility insights have proven invaluable in crisis management settings. By correlating county-level travel behavior with infection trends, planners can better anticipate waves of resource demands. Ultimately, this dataset empowers effective solutions to mitigate the spread of COVID-19 and refine comprehensive emergency response strategies, while informing policy decisions.
Use-cases: Identify trends in daily travel during the COVID-19 pandemic
Pinpoint underserved regions lacking COVID-19 testing facilities
Optimize resource allocation by analyzing supply and demand
Enhance public health communication about testing availability

column_metadata.type_of_employer_application: Refers to the filing status of the application. Values include Individual Employer, Association – Sole Employer, Joint Employer; Association – Joint Employer, or Association – Agent Form ETA-9142A, Section A, Item 1.
column_metadata.type_of_housing: The type of housing that will be provided to workers at the listed housing location. Form ETA-790A, Section D, Item 6.
column_metadata.type_of_representation: Valid values include Attorney, or Agent. If blank, employer is not a being represented by an Attorney or Agent. Form ETA-9142A, Section D, Item 1.
column_metadata.wage_offer: Wage paid to workers subject to the temporary labor certification. Form ETA-790A, Section A, Item 8b.
column_metadata.website_to_apply: Website address to apply for job opportunity. Form ETA-9142A Section G, Item 4.
column_metadata.wednesday_hours: Total work hours anticipated for Wednesday. Form ETA-790A, Section A, Item 6e.
column_metadata.work_contracts_attached: If Employer is identified as H-2ALC, Y = copies of full-executed work contracts for each agricultural business attached to the application; N = work contracts are not attached to the application. Form ETA-9142A, Section E, Item 6.

Additional-information.Summary: Daily H-2A agricultural worker address data in US.
Additional-information.Description: US H-2A Temporary Agricultural Workers Summary Daily by Address provides granular insights on the location and demand for seasonal farm labor across the country. Updated daily, this dataset organizes entries by employer and includes key data on worksite addresses, job start and end dates, wage rates, and other employment conditions. It highlights the number of requested H-2A workers, certification status, as well as additional attachments that specify housing requirements or special pay conditions. Through these detailed records, stakeholders can gauge critical information such as the job titles, schedules, and compliance measures related to the H-2A program. This dataset empowers policy makers, social service organizations, and research institutions with the means to identify high-demand agricultural areas, track workforce movements, and assess local housing availability. By pinpointing these densities of migrant labor, communities can proactively mobilize social resources, including healthcare, education, and transportation assistance, tailored to worker needs. Analysts can also utilize this data to spot trends in temporary farm labor supply, forecasting needs for future planting or harvest seasons. Overall, the dataset’s structured approach offers comprehensive visibility into the H-2A workforce, facilitating data-driven decisions that benefit employers, workers, and agencies aiming to ensure fair and effective labor practices. It fosters compliance.
Use-cases: Identify high-demand agricultural regions needing labor
Assess social service or resource allocation for migrant workers
Evaluate workforce movements across various counties
Forecast future labor supply for peak planting or harvest seasons
Support data-driven policy planning and labor compliance

Additional-information.Summary: US mental health facilities & prescription details
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides a comprehensive listing of US Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA) facilities, capturing a wide array of meta-information including addresses, phone numbers, and website links. It details facility characteristics such as whether they offer detoxification, mental health services, transitional housing, or specialized programs for co-occurring substance use disorders. Additionally, it includes data on medication-assisted treatments (MAT) and prescriptive patterns, such as the number of prescriptions, unique drugs, and total drug costs associated with each facility's National Provider Identifier (NPI). By merging location data with prescribing metrics, stakeholders can gain insights into regional coverage, service availability, and potential underserved areas. Healthcare organizations, policymakers, and insurers can leverage this information to monitor capacity constraints, identify potential gaps in care, and implement targeted interventions. Researchers and public health officials can analyze usage trends to determine relationships between prescription volumes and community needs. Furthermore, pharmaceutical experts can harness prescribing patterns to drive strategic planning and marketing efforts. Collectively, this dataset represents a critical resource for facilitating improved public health outcomes, identifying disparities, and guiding resource allocation and policy decisions that bolster the mental health infrastructure throughout the United States. Its integration with broader data fosters overall robust healthcare coordination.
Use-cases: Pinpoint facility locations to identify community coverage gaps
Target high-prescribing areas for pharmaceutical marketing campaigns
Analyze prescription volumes to detect potential fraud or abuse
Evaluate over-prescription or under-prescription trends across regions
Inform healthcare policy and resource allocation decisions

name: Clinical Trials Contact Information

column_metadata.standardized_date: Ingestion date

Extracted-text.structure: Researchers analyze (study) the data they collect from participants based on the research plan to answer their research questions. Different countries have different rules about how researchers can use each type of data. The informed consent form describes what researchers plan to do with participants’ data. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with key columns including city and state identifiers, various drug-related metrics (e.g., total beneficiaries, total drug cost, unique generics), and temporal data (e.g., max year, min year). The primary key consists of the city, state, and variable columns.

Additional-information.Summary: Contact info for the clinical trial references set
Additional-information.Description: The 'Clinical Trials Contact Information' dataset offers comprehensive contact details for researchers, sponsors, and administrative staff involved in various clinical studies. It includes records identifying city and state locations, along with vital drug-related metrics such as total beneficiaries, total drug cost, and unique generics. Temporal information encompassing maximum and minimum years helps stakeholders analyze trends over time, while the primary key is formed by city, state, and variable columns. Researchers leverage these fields to understand patterns within clinical research, ensuring proper data usage and compliance with informed consent guidelines. Additionally, pharmaceutical companies can identify regions with higher prescription demands and optimize their product distribution strategies accordingly. Healthcare policymakers use the information to allocate resources effectively, targeting areas in need of specific medical interventions or improved patient support programs. Insurance companies benefit by assessing regional risk profiles based on medication usage patterns and tailoring coverage plans for diverse populations. This dataset’s structure ensures comparability across multiple locations, enabling broad-scale analyses of clinical behaviors and outcomes. By integrating contact information with usage data, organizations can accurately track study progress, recruit participants, and refine future trials. Ultimately, this resource fosters collaboration across the clinical research ecosystem, improving decision-making, treatment strategies, and patient outcomes.
Use-cases: Pharmaceutical Market Analysis
Healthcare Policy Planning
Insurance Risk Assessment

name: Clinical Trials Eligibility Information

column_metadata.eligibility_criteria: A limited list of criteria for selection of participants in the clinical study, provided in terms of inclusion and exclusion criteria and suitable for assisting potential participants in identifying clinical studies of interest. Use a bulleted list for each criterion below the headers Inclusion Criteria and Exclusion Criteria
column_metadata.gender: The sex and, if applicable, gender of the participants eligible to participate in the clinical study. Note: Sex means a person's classification as male or female based on biological distinctions. All: Indicates no limit on eligibility based on the sex of participants. Female: Indicates that only female participants are being studied. Male: Indicates that only male participants are being studied.
column_metadata.gender_based: Indication whether participant eligibility is based on gender. Gender means a person's self-representation of gender identity. Yes: Eligibility is based on gender. No: Eligibility is not based on gender.
column_metadata.gender_description: If eligibility is based on gender, provide descriptive information about Gender criteria.
column_metadata.healthy_volunteers: Indication that participants who do not have a disease or condition, or related conditions or symptoms, under study in the clinical study are permitted to participate in the clinical study.
column_metadata.maximum_age: The numerical value, if any, for the maximum age a potential participant can be to be eligible for the clinical study.
column_metadata.minimum_age: The numerical value, if any, for the minimum age a potential participant must meet to be eligible for the clinical study.
column_metadata.sampling_method: The method used for sampling. Probability Sample: Exclusively random process to guarantee that each participant or population has specified chance of selection, such as simple random sampling, systematic sampling, stratified random sampling, cluster sampling, and consecutive participant sampling. Non-Probability Sample: Any of a variety of other sampling processes, such as convenience sampling or invitation to volunteer.
column_metadata.study_population: A description of the population from which the groups or cohorts will be selected (for example, primary care clinic, community sample, residents of a certain town).
