name: US Tax Exempt Organizations Locations by Address

column_metadata.acct_pd: This designates the accounting period or fiscal year ending date (Jan - Dec) of the organization (MM).
column_metadata.activity: An organization formerly listed up to three activity codes on application Forms 1023 and 1024. These are codes which reflect an organization's purposes, activities, operations, or type. From one to three activity codes may be in this field. Note: activity codes became obsolete with the adoption of the National Taxonomy of Exempt Entity (NTEE) coding system in January 1995. However, organizations determined to be exempt prior to that date will reflect the activity codes previously assigned.
column_metadata.affiliation: Affiliation Code defines the organizational grouping. See data dictionary URL for code values
column_metadata.asset_amt: Asset Amount is an amount from the most recent Form 990 series return filed by the organization. Asset Amount is the Book Value Total Assets End of Year - PART X Balance Sheet Line 16 Col. (B) shown on the Form 990. This field is also from PART II, Line 25, Col. (B) EOY on Form 990EZ and PART II, Line 16, Col. (b) on Form 990PF. This field is dollars only.
column_metadata.asset_cd: Asset Codes relate to the book value amount of assets shown on the most recent Form 990 series return filed by the organization. See data dictionary URL for code values
column_metadata.classification: Subsection Codes are the codes shown under section 501(c) of the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, which define the category under which an organization may be exempt. A table of subsection and classification codes (which reflects a further breakdown of the Internal Revenue Code subsections) can be found in the section entitled Table of EO Subsection and Classification Codes (below). One to four different classification codes may be present
column_metadata.deductibility: Deductibility Code signifies whether contributions made to an organization are deductible. See data dictionary URL for code values
column_metadata.ein: Employer Identification Number (EIN) is a nine digit number assigned by the IRS to identify a particular organization’s account.
column_metadata.filing_req_cd: This indicates the primary return(s) the organization is required to file. See data dictionary URL for code values
column_metadata.foundation: See data dictionary URL for code values
column_metadata.group: This is a four-digit internal number assigned to central/parent organizations holding group exemption letters.
column_metadata.ico: In Care Of Name is the person (officer, director, etc.) to whose attention any correspondence should be directed.
column_metadata.income_amt: Income Amount is a computer generated amount from the most recent Form 990 series return filed by the organization. Income Amount is computer generated using PART I, Total Revenue Line 12 and adding back in the expense items, i.e. Line 6b (Rental Expenses) shown on the Form 990 return. On Form 990EZ it is generated using PART I, Line 9 and adding back in the expense items, i.e. Line 5b (Cost or Other Basis Expenses). Income Amount for Form 990PF is generated using Part I, Line 10b (Cost of Goods) and adding Part I, Line 12, Col. (A) (Total Revenue Col. A) and Part IV, Line 1, Col. (G) (Cost or Other Basis). This field is dollars only.
column_metadata.income_cd: Income Codes relate to the amount of income shown on the most recent Form 990 series return filed by the organization.  See data dictionary URL for code values
column_metadata.name: Primary Name of Organization
column_metadata.ntee_cd: The National Taxonomy of Exempt Entities (NTEE) Code is a four digit code used to classify an exempt organization in terms of its primary exempt activity. A table of the codes found in the first three-digits can be found described below. The first digit (Common Code) is a modifier used to describe activities in support of nonprofit organizations. The fourth digit further defines the classification of the organization and is not defined here.
column_metadata.organization: This defines the type of organization as follows. See data dictionary URL for code values
column_metadata.revenue_amt: Amount from Form 990, Part 1, Line 12, or Part 1, Line 9, of Form 990EZ.
column_metadata.ruling: This is the month and year (YYYYMM) on a ruling or determination letter recognizing the organization's exempt status.
column_metadata.sort_name: Sort Name Line is another name under which the organization does business. Also used for trade names, chapter names, or local numbers for subordinate organizations of group rulings.
column_metadata.tax_period: This is the tax period of the latest return filed (YYYYMM).
column_metadata.location_lat: Latitude coordinate based on zip code
column_metadata.location_lon: Longitude coordinate based on zip code
column_metadata.standardized_date: Standardized date based off 'tax_period'

name: US COVID-19 Testing Locations by Address

column_metadata.agencyurl: Complete URL (including http:// or https://) of the testing site. This should be the web page that has information about the testing site, the appointment or virtual screening landing page, or the home page for the facility with contact information. In rare cases it can be a Facebook company page when that’s all that is available.
column_metadata.drive_through: Does the testing site have a drive through (Y/N)
column_metadata.end_date: The date the site is scheduled to discontinue testing or the date when the site discontinued testing (if known)
column_metadata.facilityid: Used to record a facility id when available
column_metadata.filter: Upon request from government entities hosting testing site locator maps that use this data, this field can be populated with a value to facilitate filtering the dataset to a specific subset of the data.
column_metadata.fine_print: Indicates that there is “fine print” associated with testing; i.e. the patient must agree to participate in a research study, or the patient must donate blood in order to receive a free test.
column_metadata.fulladdr: Address of the testing site, including street number, street, city, state, zip code
column_metadata.health_dept_url: The complete URL (including http:// or https://) of the health department in whose jurisdiction the site is located
column_metadata.instructions: Publicly shared instructions about the testing site
column_metadata.location: Testing location lat and long coordinates
column_metadata.municipality: Name of the city or town where the site is located
column_metadata.name: Name of the testing site.
column_metadata.numvehicles: Number of vehicles the testing site can accommodate
column_metadata.operhours: Hours the testing site is open
column_metadata.phone: Public phone number where members of the public can get more information, request an appointment, etc.
column_metadata.public_form: This field is automatically set to Yes when the record was added by submission of the public Survey123 form.
column_metadata.red_flag: Indicates that the volunteer who added the site suspects that the site is making false claims, using fraudulent or unauthorized test kits, or otherwise operating in an unethical way
column_metadata.referral_required: Indicates whether the site requires a doctor’s order
column_metadata.services_offered_onsite: Indicates whether the site offers, screening only, testing or collecting samples only, or both screening and testing
column_metadata.standardized_date: Standardized date derived from editdate field
column_metadata.start_date: The date the site is scheduled to begin testing or the date when the site began testing (if known)
column_metadata.status: The current operating status of the site
column_metadata.take_home_test: Does the site offer take home tests (Y/N)
column_metadata.test_processing: Describes where the test is processed (point-of-care [rapid test systems that can be operated by the same person who collects the sample and return results in minutes], onsite lab, offsite lab, or some combination of those for sites that offer more than one type of test)
column_metadata.testcapacity: The number of samples that can be collected per day
column_metadata.type_of_test: Type of test offered (molecular, antibody, antigen or some combination of those)
column_metadata.vehicle_required: Indicates whether a vehicle is required for testing
column_metadata.vetted: Has the testing location been vetted (Y/N)
column_metadata.vol_note: This is a space where volunteers can leave notes explaining why a site was updated.

Additional-information.Summary: Directory of COVID-19 testing site addresses, US
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides a comprehensive overview of COVID-19 testing locations across the United States, facilitating identification of accessible centers for those seeking diagnostic services. Each record includes a range of attributes describing site operations, such as contact information, appointment-only requirements, drive-through availability, location coordinates, county details, and referral needs. By standardizing essential fields like state abbreviations and FIPS codes, the dataset enables straightforward integration with other geo-demographic or healthcare datasets for deeper analysis. Researchers, public health officials, and healthcare providers can leverage this dataset to pinpoint testing coverage gaps, plan resource allocation, and enhance service delivery during infectious disease outbreaks. In addition, its structured format makes it suitable for mapping tools, enabling the public to locate the nearest testing site through user-friendly geographic interfaces. Policymakers can investigate clusters of regions lacking adequate testing infrastructure, thereby informing targeted interventions and policy solutions. Furthermore, the dataset captures operational statuses and associated guidelines, which can be regularly updated to reflect evolving public health requirements and site closures. Overall, these details help ensure that communities nationwide can stay informed about critical testing options, ultimately supporting efforts to control transmission rates, protect collective health, and address ongoing and future public health challenges and logistical constraints.
Use cases: Identify coverage gaps and underserved communities
Improve resource allocation and local planning efforts
Integrate with mapping tools to direct individuals to nearest test site
Support policy decisions regarding expansions and closures
Enhance outbreak preparedness and real-time response strategies

Organizations across public and private sectors can integrate this dataset into GIS platforms, enabling location intelligence, route optimization, and logistic strategies around medical, educational, and crisis-response resources. Overall, these data empower spatial analysis, bridging knowledge gaps about facilities and driving community resilience. The dataset underpins decision-making for various users, from healthcare providers to educators and policymakers, aiming to improve welfare.

Extracted-text.structure: Derived from 'us_city_job_postings' SR Table(s) Additional Structure Details: The data is structured by various geographic granularities, such as State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group. Each variable is represented as its own column. Key columns include geographic identifiers (e.g., state, county, census_tract, block_group), demographic variables (e.g., population, age, sex), housing characteristics (e.g., tenure, mortgage status, rent costs), and occupation details (e.g., specific occupations by age and sex).

Additional-information.Summary: Aggregated US county-level job postings dataset. (2023).
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides comprehensive county-level insights into job postings across the United States, derived from the underlying “us_city_job_postings.” It consolidates robust workforce data for better understanding of labor dynamics, applicant demographics, and occupational distributions. Each record encompasses standardized geographic identifiers, capturing critical information like state, county, and census tract. The dataset also contains numerous demographic fields, including population size, age brackets, and gender breakdown. Housing characteristics are similarly outlined, detailing mortgage status, rent data, and tenure classifications. Additionally, this resource covers occupation-related variables, detailing the segments of local job markets, thereby helping employers and recruiters gain targeted visibility into prospective candidate pools. The data’s breadth makes it essential for various decision-making processes. Real estate firms may correlate local workforce availability with suitable housing stock, driving more informed site selection. Policymakers benefit from these metrics to shape public policy and urban planning strategies aimed at bolstering community development. Human resource executives can pinpoint emerging workforce trends, expedite recruitment, and strategically allocate resources. Researchers will discover patterns useful for economic forecasting and modeling of labor supply. By offering granular levels down to block group, stakeholders can effectively harness county-level job posting data to implement data-driven actions aligned with local economic realities effectively.
Use-cases: Real Estate Market Analysis
Workforce Planning
Public Policy and Urban Planning

Extracted-text.structure: Annual State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of health insurance based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured at various geographic levels including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group. Key columns include geographic identifiers (state, county, census_tract, block_group, zcta), demographic variables (household size, family structure, marriage status), and metadata fields (fileid, stusab, chariter, sequence, logrecno).

Additional-information.Summary: ACS data on insured across multiple US geographies
Additional-information.Description: This dataset provides annual five-year estimates from the American Community Survey (ACS) for health insurance coverage and associated demographic variables at multiple geographic resolutions, including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group. It illuminates patterns in household structure, marriage status, and family composition, thus offering robust granularity to policymakers, businesses, and researchers. The data can reveal how insurance coverage correlates with various social, economic, and demographic factors. It also helps identify areas with potentially underinsured populations, guiding targeted interventions or policy changes. This resource is particularly useful in analyzing community health needs, forecasting potential demands on local healthcare systems, and informing strategies to expand coverage or reduce disparities. By examining the distribution of household size, marital status, and overall demographic composition, stakeholders can tailor social services, marketing initiatives, and infrastructure investments to the needs of diverse communities. The dataset is updated with standardized date references and includes geographical codes to facilitate data mapping and integration with other sources. Its granular breakdown, combined with columns detailing plumbing, kitchen, vehicle availability, and monthly costs, broadens the scope of application for housing and economic insights. Ultimately, it fosters more informed decision making at every level of governance and industry and research outcomes.
Use-cases: Market Segmentation: Target potential customers based on insurance status, family size, and income characteristics.
Urban Planning: Allocate community resources and design infrastructure projects that address varying coverage gaps.
Policy Making: Formulate programs that focus on improving health insurance penetration in underserved areas.

Extracted-text.structure: Dataset is geo-coded at the zip-level and NAICS codes descriptions are added. Each loan is its own row with description variables such as loan amount, location, lender, business, and more as columns Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with geographic and demographic information at various levels of granularity, including state, county, ZCTA5, census tract, and block group. Key columns include geographic identifiers (e.g., state, county, census_tract, block_group), demographic attributes (e.g., population), and detailed occupation codes (e.g., b24124_246, b24125_001). The primary key is a combination of logrecno and stusab.

Additional-information.Summary: Granular daily data on U.S. PPP loans by ZIP code.
Additional-information.Description: These daily loan-level records detail the distribution and characteristics of Paycheck Protection Program (PPP) funds across the United States, aggregated by ZIP code. Each record represents a single loan, capturing business details (e.g., name, type, NAICS code), loan amounts, lender information, along with crucial metrics, such as jobs retained. The dataset is geocoded at multiple levels, including ZIP code, county, and census tract, enabling robust spatial analysis. Data points also incorporate demographic variables and occupation codes, offering insights into the diverse workforce impacted by PPP loans. Researchers can identify trends in loan allocation, track the degree of reliance on these government-backed funds, and evaluate the impact on small business stability across different regions. In addition, investigating loan approval dates and standardized metrics reveals how rapidly disparities may appear or subside over time. This dataset is valuable for public policy officials, financial agencies, and analysts seeking to measure business resiliency and refine crisis response strategies. Private enterprises can also utilize these insights to gauge economic activity, identify high-growth markets, and determine where targeted interventions might be needed most. In essence, this resource supports evidence-based decision-making for resilient economic recovery and equitable resource distribution. Reviewing industry segments yields awareness of local priorities.
Use-cases: Identify businesses relying on PPP loans during COVID
Analyze geographic distribution and loan density across industries
Evaluate job retention and regional economic impact
Conduct real estate market analysis with demographic context
Develop targeted public policy and urban planning strategies
Optimize retail and service location planning based on demand

Extracted-text.structure: Data is structured at a state and NAICS code level that contains the question asked within the survey and the response received Additional Structure Details: The data is structured at various geographic levels including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group. Key columns include geographic identifiers (e.g., state, county, census_tract, block_group), demographic information (e.g., population), and detailed occupation data (e.g., b24124_001 to b24124_490). The primary key for the dataset is a combination of logrecno and stusab.

Additional-information.Summary: Daily snapshot of small business sentiment & more.
Additional-information.Description: US Small Business Pulse Survey (SBPS) offers a timely read on the state of small businesses across the United States, capturing critical information at various geographic levels—state, county, ZIP code, census tract, and block group. The dataset encompasses a comprehensive range of metrics, including demographics, occupation details, and survey responses. Each record is anchored by a primary key combining logrecno and stusab, ensuring robust data integrity. SBPS highlights how businesses adapt to shifting market conditions and external shocks, such as COVID-19, providing insights into production changes, financial challenges, and government assistance. Analysts can segment responses by NAICS two-digit sectors, enabling precise sector-level analyses. These indicators guide policymakers, researchers, and owners seeking to understand recovery pace, obstacles, and resource needs in local economies. By leveraging SBPS, stakeholders can identify trends, develop data-driven strategies, and allocate funds effectively. Standard errors enhance transparency, allowing rigorous statistical checks and reducing misinterpretation. As a result, SBPS is a vital resource for real-time monitoring of small business sentiment nationwide. Its dynamic nature ensures timely updates that reflect prevailing conditions and emerging challenges, offering invaluable input for targeted decision-making and strategic planning in today’s fast-changing economic landscape, benefiting stakeholders at federal, state, and local levels alike nationwide.
Use-cases: Monitor and analyze COVID-19 impacts on small businesses
Assess shifts in production and overall business sentiment
Evaluate usage of financial assistance programs
Inform strategic policymaking and resource allocation
Conduct targeted market research to identify emerging trends
Support urban planning and community development initiatives
Guide public policy decisions based on real-time economic signals

Extracted-text.structure: Each row is a specific region and date while the various mobility methods are listed as columns Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with geographic and demographic information at various levels of granularity, including state, county, ZCTA5, census tract, and block group. Key columns include geographic identifiers (state, county, census tract, block group, zcta), demographic variables (population, age groups, sex), and specific attributes related to group quarters population (e.g., b26101_001 to b26101_214). The data also includes a standardized date and location coordinates.

Additional-information.Summary: Daily global mobility changes segmented by region.
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, known as the Google Mobility Report, offers daily insights into population movement trends across regions worldwide. Each record corresponds to a specific area and date, detailing how visits and time spent at various categories of places — including retail, recreation, groceries, pharmacies, parks, transit stations, workplaces, and residences — compare to a baseline established before the COVID-19 pandemic. Reported as percent changes, these figures enable users to measure how mobility patterns evolve over time. Geographic identifiers range from countries to subregions, including states and counties within the United States. Alongside location details, demographic variables like population enable a comprehensive analysis of how local factors shape daily activity. A standardized date field ensures consistent temporal alignment. By integrating these mobility indicators with demographic information, researchers, businesses, and policymakers can make data-driven decisions regarding resource allocation, marketing strategies, and urban planning. Furthermore, the dataset’s global coverage allows for cross-regional comparisons, identifying behavioral patterns and potential correlations with external factors, such as public health directives or economic conditions. Overall, the Google Mobility Report presents a robust resource for understanding shifts in human movement, providing valuable context for assessing social distancing measures, economic recovery, community behavior, and planning priorities on multiple scales.
Use-cases: Assess daily changes in consumer foot traffic across regions
Identify trends in high and low travel days for planning
Support marketing campaigns and product placement
Guide civic infrastructure and urban planning decisions
Optimize healthcare outreach by analyzing commuting patterns

column_metadata.assistance_transaction_unique_key: System-generated database key used to uniquely identify each financial assistance transaction record and facilitate record lookup, correction, and deletion. A concatenation of AwardingSubTierAgencyCode, FAIN, URI, CFDA_Number, and AwardModificationAmendmentNumber with a single underscore character inserted in between each. If a field is blank, it is recorded as '-none-'.
column_metadata.assistance_award_unique_key: System-generated database key used to uniquely identify each financial award record and facilitate record lookup, correction, and deletion.
column_metadata.award_id_fain: The Federal Award Identification Number (FAIN) is the unique ID within the Federal agency for each (non-aggregate) financial assistance award.
column_metadata.modification_number: The identifier of an action being reported that indicates the specific subsequent change to the initial award.
column_metadata.award_id_uri: Unique Record Identifier of the award id
column_metadata.sai_number: A number assigned by state (as opposed to federal) review agencies to the award during the grant application process.
column_metadata.federal_action_obligation: Amount of Federal governments obligation, de-obligation, or liability for an award transaction.
column_metadata.total_obligated_amount: This is a system generated element providing the sum of all the amounts entered in the Action Obligation field for a particular PIID and Agency. Example: Contract has 9 Modifications under Transaction Number as 1 and 9 modifications with the same PIID under Transaction Number as 2. The base contracts and all the modifications have Action Obligation as usd 10 each. The value for the field Total Obligated Amount when the either of the bases or the modification is retrieved through atom feeds will be $200 ($100 under Transaction Number 1 + $100 under Transaction Number 2). Total Obligated Amount is generated irrespective of the Transaction Number on the Awards.
column_metadata.total_outlayed_amount_for_overall_award: Total outlayed amount for overall awards
column_metadata.indirect_cost_federal_share_amount: The total amount of any single Federal award action that is allocated, per the award recipient’s approved award budget, to indirect costs.
column_metadata.non_federal_funding_amount: The amount of the award funded by non-Federal source(s), in dollars. Program Income (as defined in 2 CFR 200.80) is not included until such time that Program Income is generated and credited to the agreement.
column_metadata.total_non_federal_funding_amount: The amount of the total award funded by non-Federal source(s), in dollars.
column_metadata.face_value_of_loan: The face value of the direct loan or loan guarantee.
column_metadata.original_loan_subsidy_cost: The estimated long-term cost to the Government of a direct loan or loan guarantee, or modification thereof, calculated on a net present value basis, excluding administrative costs.
column_metadata.total_face_value_of_loan: The face value of the direct loan or loan guarantee.
column_metadata.total_loan_subsidy_cost: The sum of all original subsidy costs from all transactions with the same FAIN.
column_metadata.disaster_emergency_fund_codes_for_overal: Distinguishes whether the budgetary resources, obligations incurred, unobligated and obligated balances, and outlays are classified as disaster, emergency, wildfire suppression or none of the three. (Per USSGL TFM Part 2, Section IV, Account Attribute Definition Report.)
column_metadata.outlayed_amount_from_covid-19_supplement: Represents the outlayed amount funded by COVID-19 supplementals.
column_metadata.obligated_amount_from_covid-19_supplemen: Represents the obligated amount funded by COVID-19 supplementals.
column_metadata.outlayed_amount_from_iija_supplemental_f: Outlayed amount for Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act (IIJA)
column_metadata.obligated_amount_from_iija_supplemental_: Represents the obligated amount funded by iija supplementals
column_metadata.action_date: The date the action being reported was issued or signed by the Government or a binding agreement was reached.
column_metadata.action_date_fiscal_year: The fiscal year the action being reported was issued or signed by the Government or a binding agreement was reached.
column_metadata.period_of_performance_start_date: The date on which, for the award referred to by the action being reported, awardee effort begins or the award is otherwise effective.
column_metadata.period_of_performance_current_end_date: The current date on which, for the award referred to by the action being reported, awardee effort completes or the award is otherwise ended. Administrative actions related to this award may continue to occur after this date. This date does not apply to procurement indefinite delivery vehicles under which definitive orders may be awarded.
column_metadata.awarding_agency_code: A department or establishment of the Government as used in the Treasury Account Fund Symbol (TAFS).
column_metadata.awarding_agency_name: The name associated with a department or establishment of the Government as used in the Treasury Account Fund Symbol (TAFS).
column_metadata.awarding_sub_agency_code: Identifier of the level 2 organization that awarded, executed or is otherwise responsible for the transaction.
column_metadata.awarding_sub_agency_name: Name of the level 2 organization that awarded, executed or is otherwise responsible for the transaction.
column_metadata.awarding_office_code: Identifier of the level n organization that awarded, executed or is otherwise responsible for the transaction.
column_metadata.awarding_office_name: Name of the level n organization that awarded, executed or is otherwise responsible for the transaction.
column_metadata.funding_agency_code: The 3-digit CGAC agency code of the department or establishment of the Government that provided the preponderance of the funds for an award and/or individual transactions related to an award.
column_metadata.funding_agency_name: Name of the department or establishment of the Government that provided the preponderance of the funds for an award and/or individual transactions related to an award.
column_metadata.funding_sub_agency_code: The 3-digit CGAC agency code of the department or establishment of the Government that provided the preponderance of the funds for an award and/or individual transactions related to an award.
column_metadata.funding_sub_agency_name: Name of the department or establishment of the Government that provided the preponderance of the funds for an award and/or individual transactions related to an award.

column_metadata.funding_office_name: Name of the level n organization that provided the preponderance of the funds obligated by this transaction.

Extracted-text.structure: New files are uploaded by the 15th of each month. Check the Data As Of column to see the last time files were generated. Full files feature data for the fiscal year up until the date the file was prepared, and delta files feature only new, modified, and deleted data since the date the last month's files were generated. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured at various geographic levels including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group. Key columns include geographic identifiers (e.g., state, county, tract, blkgrp), housing cost metrics (e.g., b25106_001 to b25106_046), and demographic information (e.g., population, household income). The primary key is a combination of logrecno and stusab.

Additional-information.Summary: Tracks US assistance spending at a granular scale
Additional-information.Description: Federal Government Spending on Assistance Transactions (USAspending) is a comprehensive dataset detailing federal funding obligations and outlays across the United States. Updated regularly, it provides insights into how public dollars flow to diverse recipients, including state agencies, nonprofit organizations, and private entities. The dataset supports transparency and promotes accountability by displaying crucial elements such as award amounts, key dates, and recipient attributes. Spanning multiple geographies— from national to local levels— it highlights spending distributions to states, counties, and even ZIP codes. This broad coverage allows analysts, researchers, and policymakers to evaluate the effectiveness of government programs, identify potential areas of fraud or waste, and influence the efficient allocation of resources. Additionally, stakeholders can cross-reference the data with demographic, socio-economic, or environmental indicators, facilitating multifaceted research. The dataset includes unique identifiers for each transaction, ensuring accurate tracking, corrections, and deletions. Information about awarding and funding agencies, sub-agencies, and relevant offices offers a granular view of government activities. By capturing an array of assistance transaction characteristics, the dataset helps shape data-driven decisions in fields like housing, social services, or economic development. As such, it stands as a critical repository for assessing the impact of federal spending across local communities and fosters collaboration.
Use-cases: Ensuring taxpayer transparency into government expenditures
Real estate market analysis and regional housing assessments
Informing urban planning and development initiatives
Guiding policy making and targeting social service programs

Extracted-text.structure: Annual State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of education based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured at various geographic levels including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group. Key columns include geographic identifiers (e.g., state, county, tract, blkgrp), income-related fields (e.g., b06010_001 to b06010_055), and poverty status fields (e.g., b06012_001 to b06012_020). The primary key is a combination of logrecno and stusab.

Additional-information.Summary: 2018 ACS 5-year education data for US geographies.
Additional-information.Description: 2018 ACS 5-year education data for US geographies provides annual educational attainment distributions across multiple geographic levels including state, county, ZCTA5, census tract, and block group. The dataset includes key columns for geographic identifiers, income-based fields, and measures of poverty status. By combining educational attainment with economic variables, researchers, policymakers, and organizations can glean insights into local populations’ educational profiles and their correlation with socio-economic conditions. This data is particularly valuable for market research, policy-making, and real estate strategies that depend on understanding how education and income intersect across diverse communities. The 2018 ACS 5-year estimates are derived from robust sample surveys, ensuring statistically reliable metrics. Users can further investigate patterns by linking age cohorts to educational achievement, quantifying potential workforce readiness or identifying areas needing additional resources for economic development. This dataset supports both historical trend analysis and snapshots at granular levels, making it essential for local planning, academic research, and community health initiatives. The standardized date in the dataset references the first day of 2018, ensuring temporal consistency. Overall, this dataset serves as a foundation for data-driven decisions involving educational access, socio-economic uplift, and targeted interventions across the United States. It also fulfills various compliance or auditing needs.
Use-cases: Market research and targeting
Policy making and social programs
Real estate and urban planning
Academic research and community development

Extracted-text.structure: The data is structured by various geographic granularities which a user can choose from with each variable being its own column.   Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with multiple columns representing various demographic attributes and geographic identifiers. Key columns include "logrecno" (Logical Record Number), "stusab" (State Postal Abbreviation), "population" (Population for geographic area), and "standardized_date" (Standardized date based on the first day of 2018). The data is organized at different geographic granularities such as state, county, ZCTA5, census tract, and block group levels.

Additional-information.Summary: Hyperlocal housing & job data from ACS 2018 block group
Additional-information.Description: The 'US American Community Survey (ACS) 2018: Series 21 Housing and Occupation Statistics - Block Group' dataset offers comprehensive, hyperlocal insights into American housing attributes at the block group level. By combining data on housing characteristics, mortgage and renting patterns, and detailed occupational breakdowns for full-time, year-round employed populations, this resource enables analysts, policymakers, and businesses to explore nuanced community profiles. Key indicators include the number of rooms per housing unit, occupancy status, mortgage vs. renting structure, and the distribution of occupation types, focusing particularly on female full-time employees across various industries. Researchers can also segment data based on race and ethnicity to identify inequalities and inform targeted interventions. Geographical variables such as state, county, census tract, and block group codes help users pinpoint localized trends or shifts in real estate and occupational environments. Whether assessing home affordability or workforce composition, this dataset provides the granular context necessary for data-driven decision-making. Urban planners, for instance, can allocate public resources more effectively, while businesses can refine location-based strategies. Public health entities might cross-reference these housing and occupation metrics with health data to better serve specific demographics. Overall, the dataset’s breadth and depth empower multidimensional analysis of America’s housing and economic ecosystem.
Use-cases: Hyper-local real estate analysis
Mortgage and rent trends for financial forecasts
Identify occupational distribution and labor shortages
Urban planning resource allocation
Public health and social equity analysis

Additional-information.Summary: 2018 ACS: Family structure & household details set
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, officially named the US American Community Survey (ACS) 2018: Series 8, offers comprehensive household-level demographic information captured through five-year estimates. It breaks down aspects such as marriage status, household type, presence of children, and extended family composition across diverse geographic subdivisions including states, counties, ZIP Code Tabulation Areas (ZCTAs), census tracts, and block groups. By analyzing variables like marital status, parent-child relationships, and household size, the dataset helps identify patterns related to living arrangements, family dynamics, and socioeconomic contexts. For instance, city planners can reference these distributions of household size and family structure to guide infrastructure improvements and public service delivery. Marketers can target campaigns by examining certain demographics, such as single-parent households, in a specific location. Healthcare providers can strategically plan outreach programs in areas with high concentrations of a particular age group or marital status pattern. The dataset, which is compiled and standardized for 2018, also includes race-specific household type metrics, enabling intersectional analysis across demographic indicators. With the presence of standardized geographic identifiers, including block group and tract FIPS codes, data users can slice and exponentiate insights at granular levels. This offers a multi-dimensional perspective valuable for evidence-based policymaking, academic research, and business intelligence. Overall.

Extracted-text.structure: Annual State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of housing,structure,rent,mortgage based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured in a tabular format with 13 key columns. The primary key is a combination of the "laus_area_code" and "period" columns. Key columns include "laus_area_code" (Local Area Unemployment Statistics Area Code), "state_fips_code" (State FIPS Code), "county_fips_code" (County FIPS Code), "area_title" (Area Name), "period" (Time Period), "civilian_labor_force" (Number of labor force), "employed" (Number of employed labor force), "unemployed_level" (Number of unemployed labor force), "unemployed_rate" (Unemployment rate), "is_preliminary" (Indicates if data is preliminary), "location_lat" (Latitude), "location_lon" (Longitude), and "standardized_date" (Standardized date).

Additional-information.Summary: Housing distribution data from ACS 2018: Series 19
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, titled US American Community Survey (ACS) 2018: Series 19, provides annual housing structure, mortgage, and rent distribution data from the ACS five-year estimates. It covers geographic levels ranging from state and county to smaller entities such as Census Tracts and Block Groups. With its 13 key columns, it also includes essential identifiers like FIPS codes, area descriptions, and location coordinates. Researchers and analysts utilize this dataset to explore housing affordability, rental trends, and mortgage status patterns across multiple regions. By merging population totals and demographic details, the data can reveal potential areas of housing shortages or surpluses, and can help in analyzing shifts in property investment strategies. The dataset’s measured timeframe helps stakeholders track changes from year to year, while standardized dates and the presence of geographic coordinates facilitate integration with other relevant data sources. The robust coverage of housing-related variables, including monthly rent, mortgage payments, and property value estimates, allows for a comprehensive view of residential patterns. Whether examining suburban, urban, or rural contexts, this dataset enables robust comparisons among diverse localities. It is valuable for policymakers, real estate professionals, and community organizations seeking to understand the interplay between housing costs, household characteristics, and broader economic conditions.
Use-cases: Analyzing housing affordability and mortgage trends across regions
Informing real estate development and investment decision-making
Assessing rental market conditions to guide community planning
Evaluating policy impacts on housing costs and neighborhood vitality

Extracted-text.structure: Annual State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of housing,tenure,occupancy based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured as a time series with daily records for each county in the USA. Key columns include countyfips (County FIPS Code), county_name (Name of the county), state (State abbreviation), statefips (State FIPS Code), date (Date of the record), deaths (Total deaths from COVID-19), confirmed_cases (Total confirmed cases of COVID-19), location_lat (Latitude of the county), location_lon (Longitude of the county), and standardized_date (Standardized date in yyyy-MM-dd format). The primary key is a combination of countyfips and standardized_date.

Additional-information.Summary: US ACS 2018:housing, tenure, and occupancy by area
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, known as 'US American Community Survey (ACS) 2018: Series 18,' offers comprehensive housing-related metrics for State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group levels. Derived from ACS five-year estimates, it focuses on distributions concerning housing, tenure, and occupancy. The data points include crucial metrics like the share of owner-occupied homes, rental rates, and vacancy details, which can help stakeholders to analyze community-level housing trends. Researchers, policymakers, and business analysts rely on this dataset to identify demographic shifts, study household formation patterns, and understand the interplay between housing supply and demand at various geographic scales. The standardized structure provides daily records for each county, capturing key fields such as FIPS codes, location coordinates, and population figures. Although it was originally designed with housing tenure in mind, this data can also inform broader socioeconomic and public health assessments, helping governmental and private entities alike to plan for infrastructure, healthcare distribution, and resource allocation. By offering a granular viewpoint into local living conditions, this dataset forms a basis for further research on housing affordability, changes in household size, and neighborhood composition. Ultimately, it represents a vital resource for guiding data-driven decisions about community development and population well-being. It fosters informed policy.
Use-cases: Housing Market Analysis
Public Health Policy Planning
Infrastructure Investment Strategies
Economic Impact Analysis
Healthcare Capacity Management

Extracted-text.structure: Annual State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of housing,home value based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with key columns including zip code (zip), zip code name (name), total mid-march employees (emp), total first quarter payroll (qp1), total annual payroll (ap), total number of establishments (est), and survey year (year). Additional columns include noise flags for payroll and employment data, city and state information, and geographic coordinates.

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2018 data on housing & home value distribution
Additional-information.Description: This ACS dataset from the year 2018 provides in-depth data on housing and home value metrics for all U.S. States, counties, census tracts, ZCTA5, and block groups. It aggregates five-year estimates, covering distributions of home values, occupant demographics, and property aspects such as mortgage status or housing units. Accessible to researchers, policy-makers, and businesses, these comprehensive metrics can guide decisions on real estate investments, product targeting, and socio-economic programs. The dataset includes geospatial information, such as FIPS codes, latitudes, and longitudes, to allow detailed spatial analyses and mapping. With standardized columns for population counts, wages, and employment figures, data users can merge these records with other economic indicators to evaluate multifaceted market conditions. This dataset also tracks the presence of noise flags for confidentiality compliance, ensuring sensitive information is protected. By offering granular insights, from large geographic areas down to block groups, it makes it possible for organizations to tailor strategies to unique local conditions. Diverse industries ranging from retail to government agencies can utilize this dataset to assess community needs, forecast potential consumer demand, and plan resource allocation. Ultimately, this ACS 2018 dataset is a key resource for any stakeholder requiring accurate housing-related intelligence. Its scope aids strategic decisions.
Use-cases: Identifying housing markets with specific value ranges
Conducting localized real estate investment analysis
Integrating home value data with other socioeconomic indicators
Guiding policy initiatives for housing and community development

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2018: group quarters & coverage, Series 27
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, titled US American Community Survey (ACS) 2018: Series 27, provides detailed estimates at multiple geographic levels (state, county, ZCTA5, census tract, and block group). Key measures include group quarters population, institutional vs. noninstitutional distributions, mortgage status, and health insurance coverage compiled from the ACS five-year estimates. By breaking out the population into specific categories—such as adult correctional facilities, nursing facilities, student housing, and more—users can conduct nuanced analyses of different residential arrangements and their demographic profiles. The dataset also pinpoints gender and age breakdowns across these various living arrangements, making it possible to study both the overall population and the unique needs of subpopulations. In addition, columns describing mortgage and insurance status offer insights into housing stability and healthcare accessibility. Each record links to FIPS codes or ZCTA codes to support accurate geographic mapping and cross-dataset aggregation. This thorough layout is particularly beneficial for organizations, government agencies, and researchers interested in understanding how demographic segments vary by region. Armed with these insights, policymakers can shape more targeted interventions, from resource allocation in public health to strategies for housing assistance. In essence, this series provides a comprehensive lens on American communities and their living conditions.
Use-cases: Analyze housing stability and mortgage penetration rates at local levels.
Identify regions with high institutional or noninstitutional group quarters populations for targeted policy interventions.
Examine health insurance coverage gaps across different demographic segments.
Compare population structures by age, gender, and living arrangements to inform public service planning.
Support academic research on socioeconomic conditions linked to group quarters and household populations.

Additional columns provide details on employment size classes and noise flags for data suppression.

Extracted-text.structure: Annual State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of housing based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured at the census tract level, with each tract identified by a unique FIPS code. Key columns include demographic and socioeconomic indicators such as poverty rate, unemployment rate, per capita income, percentage of households with no vehicle, and percentage of minority populations. The data also includes geographic coordinates (latitude and longitude) for spatial analysis.

Additional-information.Summary: 2018 ACS data for rent, ownership, property values
Additional-information.Description: This dataset comprises 2018 American Community Survey (ACS) five-year estimates at multiple geographical levels, including State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group. It focuses on housing metrics such as median home value, gross rent, mortgage status, and household income distributions. The data captures details about the year structures were built, age of householder, household size, and heating fuel usage. With these diverse variables, analysts can explore housing affordability, examine market trends, evaluate income-based housing disparities, and study the interplay between demographic and housing indicators. By offering granular geographic coverage, the dataset supports detailed neighborhood-level analysis of community housing conditions. Additionally, specialized columns measure property attributes like median value by household move-in date and year of construction. Users gain a comprehensive perspective of housing stock composition, costs, and socio-economic drivers that influence rent and ownership patterns. Researchers, policymakers, and businesses can leverage these insights to guide affordable housing initiatives, analyze rental market fluctuations, identify real estate investment opportunities, and predict future housing needs based on demographic shifts. Overall, this resource enables a robust examination of how housing markets adapt to changing economic and social factors, providing a foundation for evidence-based decision-making. In addition, it helps identify gaps in homeownership equity.
Use-cases: Assess local housing affordability and develop policy measures
Facilitate real estate investment strategy with median value insights
Guide community development programs to address housing disparities
Evaluate demographic changes for future housing demand forecasting

Extracted-text.structure: The data is structured by various geographic granularities which a user can choose from with each variable being its own column.   Additional Structure Details: The data is structured as a table with key columns including facility location (latitude and longitude), facility type (e.g., pharmacy, dialysis center, community health center), and status (open, closed, not participating, unknown). Other important columns include the facility name, address, city, state, zip code, and standardized date of data ingestion.

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2018 data on household/family in the US census
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, known as the 2018 ACS Series 7, covers household and family structure across states, counties, ZCTAs, census tracts, and block groups. It provides detailed data on relationships, living arrangements, presence of children, and extended families. Policymakers, agencies, and researchers use these metrics to assess household composition, evaluate child care needs, and identify regions needing social services. By examining median wages, employment status, and occupations, users can analyze economic trends and workforce characteristics. This dataset also highlights poverty indicators, reliance on public assistance, and multi-generational homes. Emergency planners reference population density and family size data for resource allocation. Healthcare analysts use child, senior, and dependent distribution figures to optimize medical services. Accessibility to education, from preschools through adult learning, can be inferred by correlating children’s ages with school data. Overall, the 2018 ACS Series 7 offers a broad view of American families, guiding policy, research, and community initiatives. It helps stakeholders track changing domestic patterns, informing effective planning and program development. By integrating these insights, local governments and nonprofits can refine initiatives to address housing affordability, child welfare, and senior support. Ultimately, this resource fosters data-driven strategies that strengthen diverse communities nationwide, ensuring adaptable, inclusive frameworks for future growth.
Use-cases: Assess annual state, county, ZCTA5, census tract, and block group level distributions of employment status, median wages, and occupation types.
Healthcare resource allocation: Identify underserved regions lacking adequate EMS or healthcare facilities.
Emergency response planning: Optimize deployment of services based on population density and household composition.
Public health analysis: Correlate household characteristics with health outcomes to inform targeted interventions.

Extracted-text.structure: The data is structured by various geographic granularities which a user can chose from with each variable being its own column.   Additional Structure Details: The dataset is structured with each row representing a hospital facility. Key columns include "name" (hospital name), "address" (street address), "city" (city name), "state" (state name), "zip" (zip code), "type" (type of hospital), "beds" (number of beds), "owner" (ownership type), "latitude" (latitude coordinate), and "longitude" (longitude coordinate).

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2018 commuting patterns for US mobility
Additional-information.Description: This dataset, “census_acs_us_series_6_2018,” offers American Community Survey (ACS) 2018 data focusing on commuting behaviors. It provides details on how workers typically travel, including public transportation usage, carpooling, walking, biking, or driving alone, as well as the time they leave home and the duration of their commute. The dataset is structured with numerous variables that break down patterns by demographic factors, such as sex, age, and race, while also referencing geographic identifiers like block groups. By capturing granular travel details, it enables researchers, policymakers, and businesses to better understand local mobility issues, measure congestion levels, or investigate the correlation between transportation choices and socio-economic factors. This resource is invaluable for transportation planning, sustainability analysis, or assessing the potential for new infrastructure projects. The geographic detail also supports robust place-based approaches, allowing for localized insights into worker behavior. Furthermore, the dataset ensures coverage of multiple transportation modes, capturing shifts in mobility patterns. As it dates back to 2018, it offers a pre-pandemic benchmark for subsequent comparisons. Users can customize their analyses by pulling only the columns and geographies most relevant to a project. Ultimately, “census_acs_us_series_6_2018” fosters data-driven decisions in both urban and rural contexts, contributing to more efficient and equitable transportation networks.
Use-cases: Analyze daily commute modes across demographics
Assess infrastructure needs for public transit expansions
Support urban and rural transportation policy decisions
Measure traffic congestion and commute durations
Identify opportunities for carpool or rideshare initiatives
Benchmark pre-pandemic mobility patterns for longitudinal studies

Extracted-text.structure: Annual State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of Median Income & Poverty Status by Place of Birth based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured around clinical research studies and their sponsors. Key columns include "name" (sponsor name), "class" (sponsor type), "nctid" (unique identifier for each clinical trial), and "standardized_date" (date of data ingestion).

Extracted-text.structure: Annul State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of Place of Birth, Citizenship status by Age, Sex, Income & Educational Status based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with key columns including "name" (name of the clinical trial site), "state" (state where the trial is conducted), "country" (country where the trial is conducted), "zip" (zip code of the trial site), "city" (city where the trial is conducted), "nctid" (unique identifier for the clinical trial), "status" (current status of the trial), and "standardized_date" (date of data ingestion).

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2018: Place of Birth, Citizenship, Sex, Income
Additional-information.Description: This dataset compiles American Community Survey (ACS) 2018 five-year estimates offering comprehensive insights into demographics and migration patterns. It contains annual distributions across states, counties, ZIP Code Tabulation Areas, census tracts, and block groups, capturing place of birth, citizenship status, sex, income, and educational attainment. By analyzing these metrics, organizations can identify trends, address economic and social challenges, and plan resource allocation. Policymakers may use the data to track community well-being, while healthcare providers could map population shifts to plan services effectively. Researchers can explore relationships among nativity, income, and educational levels, uncovering potential inequities impacting communities. Similarly, local governments and commercial entities can determine resource needs and guide economic development strategies using these statistics. With variables detailing American Indian, Alaska Native, and many other race categories, the dataset provides nuanced insights into diverse populations. It also outlines median age, poverty status, language usage, and marital status by nativity, enabling cross-sectional assessments of different groups. Moreover, the standardized structure ensures consistent referencing across geographic areas, simplifying analysis and integration with other data sources. Ultimately, these ACS 2018 outcomes help highlight population diversity, guide policy, support equitable service delivery, and fuel further academic studies in demographic change across the United States.
Use-cases: Analyzing population distribution by place of birth for policy decisions
Identifying optimal locations for new clinical trials based on demographic characteristics
Examining citizenship status trends for resource allocation
Market analysis for healthcare services in specific geographic areas
Exploring language usage and educational attainment to design community programs
Monitoring compliance and service delivery in underserved regions

Structure: Annul State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of Place of Birth, Citizenship status by Age, Sex, Income & Educational Status based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured with key columns including "name" (name of the clinical trial site), "state" (state where the trial is conducted), "country" (country where the trial is conducted), "zip" (zip code of the trial site), "city" (city where the trial is conducted), "nctid" (unique identifier for the clinical trial), "status" (current status of the trial), and "standardized_date" (date of data ingestion).

Extracted-text.structure: Annul State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of Race, Ancestry & National Origin based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured as a relational database with key columns including "name", "brief_summary", "detailed_description", "study_first_submitted", "phase", "url", "brief_title", "nctid", "status", "official_title", "last_update_posted", and "standardized_date". The primary key is "nctid".

Additional-information.Summary: ACS 2018 Series 3: Race & Ancestry data coverage.
Additional-information.Description: This dataset is part of the US American Community Survey (ACS) 2018: Series 3. It provides detailed statistics on race, ancestry, and national origin distributions across multiple geographic levels, including states, counties, ZIP Code Tabulation Areas (ZCTAs), census tracts, and block groups. By leveraging five-year estimates compiled through the ACS, this data offers insights into the composition of local populations, enabling nuanced demographic analysis. Users can explore variables such as White alone, Black or African American alone, American Indian and Alaska Native alone, Asian alone, Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander alone, and individuals identifying with multiple races. The dataset also features ancestry breakdowns for numerous groups, including European, Middle Eastern, African, Caribbean, and Latin American origins. Healthcare providers, policymakers, and community planners find this resource invaluable for aligning services and resources based on population composition. Researchers examining social equity, health disparities, and community development can benefit from the granular data. The flexible structure, organized as a relational database, facilitates integration with external resources, enabling advanced analytics and cross-referencing. The dataset provides a fundamental basis for decision-making processes that require a comprehensive understanding of the nation’s diverse demographic landscape, promoting informed initiatives and strategies that respond to local population needs.
Use-cases: Analyze racial and ethnic composition across geographic levels.
Support healthcare planning by identifying community demographics.
Inform public policy and resource allocation based on population ancestry data.
Enable market segmentation and targeted outreach for businesses or nonprofits.
Assist pharmaceutical and research organizations in locating diverse clinical trial sites.

Structure: Annul State, County, ZCTA5, Census Tract, and Block Group level distributions of Race, Ancestry & National Origin based on ACS 5 year estimates Additional Structure Details: The data is structured as a relational database with key columns including "name", "brief_summary", "detailed_description", "study_first_submitted", "phase", "url", "brief_title", "nctid", "status", "official_title", "last_update_posted", and "standardized_date". The primary key is "nctid".

Extracted-text.structure: The data is structured by various geographic granularities which a user can chose from with each variable being its own column.   Additional Structure Details: The data is structured around clinical research studies and their results. Key columns include "name" (the name of the intervention), "type" (the type of intervention), "nctid" (the unique identifier for each clinical trial), "description" (a description of the study), "other_names" (alternative names for the intervention), "arm_group_label" (labels for different groups in the study), and "standardized_date" (the date of data ingestion).

Additional-information.Summary: Block-level 2018 ACS by age, sex, race data
Additional-information.Description: 2018 ACS Series 2 provides block-level demographic detail on U.S. population by age, sex, and race, delivering granular insights for policy, planning, and business needs. Each variable is represented by separate columns, including breakdowns like b01001_001 (total population), b01001_002 (male population), and more. The dataset includes special sub-populations, offering a robust perspective on the distribution of White, Black or African American, American Indian and Alaska Native, Asian, Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander, and individuals of Two or More Races. Additional columns like b01002 cover median age data by sex. These attributes facilitate comprehensive analysis of population structure, from the youngest age groups to the oldest, across diverse racial categories. The block group granularity ensures that users can identify nuanced local variations, supporting targeted interventions or resource allocation strategies. The dataset can be integrated with geospatial data, enabling mapping and location-based analytics. Researchers, policymakers, and organizations can expand their understanding of community demographics and track potential changes over time when combined with previous or subsequent ACS releases. The standardized_date column aligns time references, and location or geo_code fields connect demographic data to relevant FIPS or ZCTA codes for consistent integration with other datasets.
Use-cases: Identify population distributions by age, sex, and race at a granular (block group) level
Support policy planning and resource allocation in targeted communities
Enable healthcare providers to assess local demographics for potential interventions
Assist pharmaceutical firms in locating areas for clinical trial recruitment
Allow regulatory agencies to monitor demographic shifts relevant to public health and safety
Provide businesses insights for market segmentation and expansion strategies

name: US BLS Monthly Labor Force by County

column_metadata.laus_area_code: Local Area Unemployment Statistics (LAUS) Area Code
column_metadata.period: Time Period of the local area unemployment statistic. (p) refers to preliminary data and data will be published in the next update cycles
column_metadata.civilian_labor_force: Number of labor force in the Area
column_metadata.employed: Number of labor force employed in the Area
column_metadata.unemployed_level: Number of labor force unemployed in the Area
column_metadata.standardized_date: First day of the month in SR Standardized format of yyyy-MM-dd

Extracted-text.structure: Labor force data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) for the United States by county for the most recent 14 months, not seasonally adjusted. Additional Structure Details: The data is structured as a database of clinical research studies, including information about their results. Key columns include "nctid" (NCT ID), "name" (Name of the condition), and "standardized_date" (Ingestion date).
